text: Autosomal dominant osteopetrosis type II is a genetic disorder characterized by the autosomal dominant inheritance of sclerosis predominantly involving the spine, pelvis and skull base, bone fragility, dental abscesses, and has material basis in mutation in the CLCN7 gene on chromosome 16p13. It is also known as Albers-Schonberg osteopetrosis or OPTA2.

Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 5 (AROP-5) is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by the formation of abnormal bone tissue, which leads to the accumulation of excessive bone in various organs and bones throughout the body. This can cause pain, difficulty breathing, and eventually death if left untreated. AROP-5 has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is caused by mutations in the OSTM1 gene located on chromosome 6q21. It is also known as infantile malignant osteopetrosis 3, and it can be diagnosed through genetic testing and imaging studies such as X-rays, CT scans, or MRI. Treatment options may include medications to manage pain or surgery to remove excess bone tissue.
Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 8 (OPTB8) is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by the inheritance of a mutated version of the SNX10 gene on chromosome 7p15.

Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 3, also known as Guibaud-Vainsel syndrome or OPTB3, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by the presence of excessive bone in the skull and other parts of the body. It is caused by mutations in the CA2 gene on chromosome 8q21. Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 3 can also be associated with renal tubular acidosis, carbonic anhydrase II deficiency, and marble brain disease.

autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by the lack of function of the TCIRG1 gene, which leads to the accumulation of excessive bone tissue.
autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 1 has an inherited disorder that affects the skeletal system and causes it to become too dense.
autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 1 is a type of osteopetrosis that occurs due to a genetic mutation in the TCIRG1 gene.
autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 1 is a rare genetic disorder that affects children and young adults, causing bone deformities and an increased risk of fractures.

Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 2, also known as OPTB2, is a genetic disorder characterized by the autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the TNFSF11 gene located on chromosome 13q14. This leads to an osteopetrosis, or abnormal bone growth, where there is a lack of osteoclasts in the body. Osteoclasts are cells responsible for breaking down old bone tissue and maintaining healthy bone structure. As a result, individuals with autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 2 have dense, solid bones that can cause various complications such as fractures, pain, and limited mobility. It is considered a mild form of osteopetrosis compared to other forms, but it still impacts the quality of life for those affected by it.

Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 4, also known as OPTB4, is a genetic disorder that affects the bones. It is characterized by abnormal bone growth and development, which can lead to problems such as fractures and an increased risk of certain types of cancer. This condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the gene for it to be expressed. The gene responsible for this disorder has been identified as CLCN7, which is located on chromosome 16p13. It is also known as infantile malignant osteopetrosis 2.

Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis type 6, also known as OPTB6, is a genetic disorder characterized by the autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the PLEKHM1 gene on chromosome 17q21.31. This condition results in an osteopetrosis, which is a bone disease where the bones become abnormally dense and hard. It can lead to various health issues including hearing loss, dental problems, and an increased risk of fractures. OPTB6 is considered to be a rare genetic disorder that affects individuals with two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent.

Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 7, also known as OPTB7, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by the inheritance of mutated genes on chromosome 18q21. It is defined as an osteopetrosis resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TNFRSF11A gene, which leads to a decrease in osteoclast activity and the accumulation of bone tissue.

Symptoms of autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 7 can include abnormal bone growth and development, leading to an increased risk of fractures and other skeletal problems. The condition is also associated with a deficiency in immunoglobulins and can affect the functioning of the immune system.

Diagnosis of autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 7 typically involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, and imaging studies such as X-rays or computed tomography (CT) scans to evaluate bone density and structure. Molecular genetic testing can also be used to identify the specific gene mutation responsible for the condition.

Treatment options for autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 7 may include medications to promote bone growth, such as bisphosphonates or teriparatide, and measures to manage pain and improve quality of life, such as physical therapy and assistive devices.

In summary, autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 7 is a rare genetic disorder that affects bone development and the immune system, and requires specialized medical care and treatment to manage its symptoms and complications.

Waardenburg syndrome type 2b is a specific subtype of Waardenburg Syndrome, characterized by certain unique features. These features include pigmentary abnormalities in the hair, skin and eyes, congenital sensorineural hearing loss, and absence of lateral displacement of the inner canthus of each eye. This condition has a genetic basis, specifically involving variation in the chromosome region 1p21-p13.3. It is also known as WS2B or Waardenburg Syndrome type IIB.

Waardenburg Syndrome Type 1 is a condition characterized by the following symptoms:

* Congenital deafness (deaf from birth)
* Pigmentation anomalies of eyes, hair, and skin
* Dystopia canthorum (a tilted or turned-in look at the outer corners of the eyebrows)
This condition is caused by a mutation in the PAX3 gene on chromosome 2q36. It is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a person has a 50% chance of inheriting the condition if one of their parents passes it on. The exact synonyms for Waardenburg Syndrome Type 1 are WS1 and Waardenburg Syndrome type I.

Waardenburg syndrome type 3 is a condition that belongs to the category of Waardenburg syndromes. It has been defined as having a combination of features including upper limb anomalies, congenital hearing loss, dystopia canthorum (a tilted or inverted eyelid), and pigmentation anomalies involving the eyes, hair, and skin. These abnormalities are believed to be caused by mutations in the PAX3 gene located on chromosome 2q36. This condition is also known as Klein-Waardenburg syndrome or WS3. Additionally, it can be referred to as Waardenburg syndrome type III or Waardenburg syndrome with upper limb anomalies.

Waardenburg syndrome type 2A is a genetic disorder that affects the development of pigmentation, hearing, and eye features. It is caused by mutations in the MITF gene on chromosome 3p13. The disorder is characterized by the absence of lateral displacement of the inner canthus of each eye and congenital sensorineural hearing loss. Additionally, there may be pigmentary abnormalities of the hair, skin, and eyes. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the MITF gene on chromosome 3p13.

Waardenburg syndrome type 2c is a genetic disorder that affects the pigmentation of hair, skin, and eyes, as well as hearing and eye alignment. It is caused by variations in the chromosome region 8p23. It is also known as WS2C or Waardenburg syndrome type IIC.

Waardenburg syndrome type 4a is a genetic disorder that affects several systems in the body. It is characterized by pigmentation abnormalities of the hair, skin, and eyes, congenital sensorineural hearing loss, and Hirschsprung disease. These symptoms are due to mutations in the EDNRB gene on chromosome 13q22.
It is also known as WS4A or Waardenburg syndrome type IVA, and it can be further specified as Waardenburg syndrome with Hirschsprung disease type 4A.

Waardenburg syndrome type 4b is a specific type of Waardenburg syndrome, characterized by pigmentary abnormalities affecting the hair, skin, and eyes, congenital sensorineural hearing loss, and Hirschsprung disease which has a genetic basis in homozygous or heterozygous mutations in the EDN3 gene located on chromosome 20q13. It is also known as WS4B, Waardenburg syndrome type IVB, and Waardenburg syndrome with Hirschsprung disease type 4B.

Waardenburg syndrome type 4C, also known as WS4C or Waardenburg syndrome with Hirschsprung disease type 4C, is a genetic disorder characterized by the presence of certain physical features such as white forelocks and hair on the forehead, blue eyes, and a unique distribution of pigmentation in the skin, hair, and eyes. Additionally, individuals with WS4C typically have congenital hearing loss and Hirschsprung disease, which is a condition in which part of the intestine is missing or does not function properly. This disorder is caused by mutations in the SOX10 gene located on chromosome 22q13.

waardenburg syndrome type 2e is a type of waardenburg syndrome.
waardenburg syndrome type 2e has definition A genetic disorder characterized by congenital absence of pigment in hair, skin and eyes, hearing loss and inner ear abnormalities, facial weakness, and developmental delay that results from mutations in the SOX10 gene on chromosome 2q33.
waardenburg syndrome type 2e has exact synonym WS2E.
waardenburg syndrome type 2e has exact synonym WS2E with or without neurological involvement.
waardenburg syndrome type 2e has exact synonym Waardenburg syndrome type IIE.
waardenburg syndrome type 2e has exact synonym hypogonadotropic hypogonadism with anosmia and deafness with or without hypopigmentation.

Gaucher's disease, type I is a genetic disorder caused by mutations in the GBA1 gene on chromosome 1q22. It is characterized by the absence of primary central nervous system involvement and has a basis in structural variants. It is also known as acid beta-glucosidase deficiency, GD I, GD1, Gaucher disease, noncerebral juvenile, GBA deficiency, and glucocerebrosidase deficiency.

Gaucher disease type II, also known as GD II or Gaucher disease, acute neuronopathic type, is a subtype of Gaucher disease characterized by rapid neurological deterioration with involvement of cranial nerves and extrapyramidal tracts. It has a basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GBA1 gene on chromosome 1q22. The exact synonyms for Gaucher disease type II include GDII, GD2, infantile cerebral Gaucher disease, and acute neuronopathic Gaucher disease.

Gaucher disease type III, also known as GD III or Chronic Neuronopathic Type, is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the metabolism of glucocerebroside in macrophages. It is characterized by later onset and slower progression of neurological deterioration compared to Gaucher disease type II, which has a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GBA1 gene on chromosome 1q22.

Gaucher's disease, also known as type 1 Gaucher's disease, is a genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to break down glucocerebroside. It can cause various symptoms, such as anemia, fatigue, bone pain, and enlarged liver and spleen. In severe cases, it can lead to damage of the nervous system and other organs in the body. Gaucher's disease is caused by a deficiency or absence of the enzyme glucocerebrosidase, which is necessary for breaking down glucocerebroside. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that to develop the condition, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent. Gaucher's disease can occur at any age, but it is more common in people of Ashkenazi Jewish descent. Treatment options for Gaucher's disease include enzyme replacement therapy, which provides the missing enzyme directly to the body, and substrate reduction therapy, which helps to reduce the amount of glucocerebroside in the body.

Atypical Gaucher's disease due to saposin C deficiency is a type of Gaucher's disease that has a basis in some structural variant. It is characterized by the absence of the enzyme saposin C, which leads to the accumulation of glucocerebroside in macrophages and other tissues, causing damage and inflammation. This can lead to symptoms such as anemia, thrombocytopenia, and fatigue, among others. It is caused by a compound heterozygous mutation in the PSAP gene on chromosome 10q22.1.

Brachydactyly preaxial hallux varus syndrome is a type of brachydactyly, which refers to the condition where an individual has shorter than normal thumbs and toes. This condition often affects both hands and feet, with the shortening being most pronounced in the metacarpals (the bones that connect the fingers to the hand), metatarsals (the bones that connect the toes to the foot), and distal phalanges (the bones that make up the ends of the fingers and toes).

Brachydactyly preaxial hallux varus syndrome is characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance, which means that it can be passed down through generations in a family. This condition is also referred to as "Christian brachydactyly" and "preaxial brachydactyly with hallux varus and thumb abduction." It's important to note that while these terms may have been used historically, they are not currently recognized medical terms, so it's best to use the term "brachydactyly preaxial hallux varus syndrome" when referring to this condition.

Ballard Syndrome is a type of brachydactyly, which is characterized by the autosomal dominant inheritance of hypoplasia of the distal phalanges of the ulnar side of the hand and shortening of one or more metacarpals but normal stature. It has some synonyms such as Ballard type brachydactyly, Pitt-Williams brachydactyly, and brachydactyly types B and E combined.

Brachydactyly type A1 is a form of brachydactyly characterized by the presence of rudimentary or fused middle phalanges of all the digits and shortened proximal phalanges of the thumbs and big toes. It is an autosomal dominant disease that has a material basis in some cases of inheritance, and it is also known as BDA1 and Farabee type brachydactyly.

Brachydactyly type A2 is a specific subtype of brachydactyly, characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of malformations of the middle phalanx of the index finger and anomalies of the second toe. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the BMPR1B gene on chromosome 4q or in the GDF5 gene on chromosome 20q11, or heterozygous duplication in a regulatory element of BMP2 on chromosome 20p12. It is also known as Mohr-Wriedt type brachydactyly and brachymesophalangy II.

Brachydactyly type A3, also known as BDA3 or brachydactyly-clinodactyly, is a specific form of brachydactyly characterized by the shortening of the middle phalanx of the fifth finger, resulting in radial curvature of the fifth finger. This condition is also sometimes referred to as brachymesophalangy V. It is one of several types of brachydactyly, which is a term used to describe a group of conditions that result in shortened fingers or toes.

Brachydactyly type A4, also known as BDA4 or Temtamy type brachydactyly, is a form of brachydactyly characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance and the presence of hypoplastic middle phalanges in the second and fifth digits. It primarily affects the toes on these two fingers, leading to a congenital talipes calcaneovalgus deformity. This condition is also known as brachymesophalangy II and V.

That is correct, brachydactyly type A6 is a form of brachydactyly characterized by short limbs, absence or hypoplasia of the second phalanges, and synostosis of the remaining phalanges. It is also known as Osebold-Remondini syndrome and brachymesophalangy with mesomelic short limbs and carpal and tarsal osseous abnormalities.

That is correct. Brachydactyly type B1, or BDB1, is a condition characterized by short middle phalanges, rudimentary or absent terminal phalanges, and nail aplasia due to a heterozygous mutation in the ROR2 gene on chromosome 9q22.

Type C brachydactyly, also known as BDC (Brachydactyly type C), is a genetic condition characterized by the underdevelopment of certain fingers and toes. It is an autosomal dominant disorder, which means that if one parent has the gene mutation, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit the condition. The BDC gene is located on chromosome 20q11 and mutations in this gene can lead to various degrees of finger and toe abnormalities.

Brachydactyly type D, also known as BDD, is a condition characterized by short and broad terminal phalanges of the thumbs and big toes. It is an autosomal dominant disease, which means that it can be passed down through generations of a family with a high probability. The gene responsible for this condition is located on chromosome 2q31.1 and mutates the HOXD13 gene.

Mononen-Karnes-Senac syndrome is a type of brachydactyly, which is a condition characterized by short and abducted thumbs and great toes. It was first described by Mononen et al in 1978. The syndrome has also been referred to as the "Mononen type" of brachydactyly.

Brachydactyly type A1b is a genetic disorder characterized by the shortened middle phalanges of all the digits and shortened proximal phalanges of the thumbs and big toes. Despite having short stature, people with this condition have normal height. The disorder has a basis in a variation in the chromosome region 5p13.3-p13.2. Another name for this condition is Brachydactyly type A1b (BDA1B).

Type B2 brachydactyly, also known as BDB2, is a specific type of brachydactyly characterized by the following features: hypoplasia or aplasia of the distal phalanges, distal symphalangism, fusion of carpal and/or tarsal bones, and partial cutaneous syndactyly. It has a genetic basis due to mutations in the NOG gene located on chromosome 17q22.

Brachydactyly type E2, also known as BDE2, is a specific type of brachydactyly characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance. It involves short stature, tooth abnormalities, and short metacarpals and metatarsals due to a heterozygous mutation in the PTHLH gene located on chromosome 12p.

Brachydactyly type A1C, also known as BDA1C, is a type of brachydactyly characterized by the presence of short fingers and toes. It is caused by mutations in the GDF5 gene on chromosome 20q11. It has been associated with certain diseases, such as diabetes and heart disease. The term "brachydactyly type A1C" refers to a specific form of brachydactyly that is caused by mutations in the GDF5 gene.

Brachydactyly type A1D, also known as BDA1D, is a form of brachydactyly characterized by having an affected limb with only five fingers and a thumb. This condition has a genetic basis, specifically due to a heterozygous mutation in the BMPR1B gene on chromosome 4q22. It is considered a type of brachydactyly, which is a general term for short finger or limb length.

Brachydactyly is a condition where one or more of the fingers or toes are significantly shorter than normal. Sugarman's brachydactyly, specifically, is characterized by a non-articulating great toe that is set dorsal and proximal to the typical position. It has an exact synonym of "brachydactyly with major proximal phalangeal shortening."

Joubert syndrome 1, also known as CORS1 and cerebellooculorenal syndrome 1, is a genetic disorder that occurs due to a mutation in the INPP5E gene on chromosome 9q34. It is characterized by abnormal development of the cerebellum and other parts of the brain, as well as problems with vision, hearing, and kidney function. The exact synonyms for Joubert syndrome 1 include CPD4, JBTS1, and cerebelloparenchymal disorder IV.
Joubert syndrome 10 is a type of Joubert syndrome that has material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance of mutation in the OFD1 gene on chromosome Xp22.2. It also has an exact synonym of JBTS10.

Joubert Syndrome 13, also known as JBTS13, is a type of Joubert syndrome that is caused by mutations in the TCTN1 gene on chromosome 12q24. This condition affects brain development and can cause problems with balance and coordination, as well as other physical and cognitive symptoms.

Joubert Syndrome 14 is a specific type of Joubert syndrome, characterized by severe mental retardation, cerebellar vermis hypoplasia, molar tooth sign on brain imaging, hypotonia, abnormal breathing pattern in infancy, and dysmorphic facial features. It is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TMEM237 gene located on chromosome 2q33. The exact synonym for Joubert Syndrome 14 is JBTS14.

Joubert syndrome 15 is a type of Joubert syndrome that has material basis in homozygous mutation in the CEP41 gene on chromosome 7q32. It is characterized by ataxia, hypotonia, delayed psychomotor development, and variable mental retardation. The exact synonym for Joubert syndrome 15 is JBTS15.

Joubert Syndrome 16, also known as JBTS16, is a type of Joubert syndrome characterized by several unique features. These include a molar tooth sign on brain imaging, oculomotor apraxia, variable coloboma, and rare kidney involvement that is caused by homozygous mutation in the TMEM138 gene on chromosome 11q. It is important to note that Joubert Syndrome 16 has a specific definition, which distinguishes it from other types of Joubert syndrome.

Joubert syndrome 17, also known as JBTS17, is a type of Joubert syndrome characterized by episodic hyperpnea, abnormal eye movements, ataxia, and global psychomotor retardation. It has a genetic basis in compound heterozygous mutations in the C5ORF42 gene on chromosome 5p13.

Joubert syndrome 18 (JBTS18) is a type of Joubert syndrome, which is characterized by the presence of a cystic macrocystic change in the hypothalamus and other regions of the brain. This condition is caused by homozygous mutation in the TCTN3 gene located on chromosome 10q24. It has also been referred to as Joubert syndrome type 18, or simply JBTS18.

Joubert Syndrome 2, also known as Cerebellooculorenal Syndrome 2 (CORES2), is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of the cerebellum and the eyes. The main symptoms include:

* Hypotonia (low muscle tone)
* Developmental delay
* Oculomotor apraxia (difficulty with eye movements)
* Breathing abnormalities
* Molar tooth sign on brain MRI

This disorder is caused by a mutation in the TMEM216 gene, which is located on chromosome 11q12.2. It is essential to diagnose and manage this condition early to help improve the quality of life for affected individuals.

Joubert syndrome type 20, also known as JBTS20, is a genetic disorder that results from compound heterozygous mutations in the TMEM231 gene on chromosome 16q23. It is part of the larger Joubert syndrome family of disorders which are characterized by cerebellar vermis hypoplasia, ataxia, and other developmental abnormalities.

JBTS20 specifically affects the balance and coordination functions of the cerebellum, leading to difficulties in walking, speech, and fine motor skills. In addition, affected individuals may experience intellectual disability, facial dysmorphism, and an increased risk of certain other neurological conditions.

It is important for those with JBTS20 to receive proper medical care and support to manage their symptoms effectively. Genetic counseling can also be beneficial for individuals and families affected by this condition.

Joubert syndrome type 21, also known as JBTS21, is a form of the condition that occurs due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CSPP1 gene on chromosome 8q13. It shares the common symptoms of Joubert syndrome, such as distinctive facial features, an irregular-shaped cerebellum and cerebellopontine angle, and a unique pattern of brain stem abnormalities, but is distinguished by its genetic basis in the CSPP1 gene.

Joubert syndrome type 22, also known as JBTS22, is a genetic disorder that arises from a homozygous mutation in the PDE6D gene on chromosome 2q37. It is one of the three types of Joubert Syndrome, which are characterized by distinctive craniofacial features and other developmental abnormalities.

Joubert syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple systems in the body, including vision, hearing, balance, and movement. It can also cause intellectual disability and an increased risk of certain types of cancer. Symptoms may vary depending on which type of Joubert Syndrome a person has, but generally include distinctive facial features such as a large head, almond-shaped eyes, and a short, broad nasal bridge.

Early diagnosis is crucial to ensure that individuals with Joubert Syndrome receive appropriate treatment and support. Genetic testing can help identify the specific type of Joubert Syndrome and inform treatment decisions. Management typically involves addressing symptoms through therapies, medications, and assistive technology, as well as providing emotional and practical support to individuals and their families.

Joubert Syndrome 23 (JS 23) is a type of Joubert syndrome that is characterized by delayed development, abnormal eye movements, and an abnormal breathing pattern. Additionally, there is a molar tooth sign on brain MRI, which indicates homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the KIAA0586 gene located on chromosome 14q23. The exact synonym of JS 23 is JBTS23.

That is correct, Joubert Syndrome Type 24, also known as JBTS24, is characterized by delayed psychomotor development and the presence of a molar tooth sign on brain MRI, which is due to homozygous mutation in the TCTN2 gene located on chromosome 12q24.

Joubert syndrome 25, also known as JBTS25, is a type of Joubert syndrome characterized by delayed psychomotor development, oculomotor apraxia, and a molar tooth sign on brain MRI, which is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CEP104 gene located on chromosome 1p36.

Joubert syndrome 26, also known as JBTS26, is a type of Joubert Syndrome characterized by global developmental delay and cerebellar hypoplasia. This condition is caused by homozygous mutation in the KIAA0556 gene on chromosome 16p12.
Joubert Syndrome 27, also known as JBTS27, is a type of Joubert Syndrome characterized by having a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the B9D1 gene located on chromosome 17p11.

Joubert syndrome type 28 (JBTS28) is a type of Joubert syndrome characterized by abnormal development or loss of cerebellar Purkinje cells, as well as other neurological symptoms such as ataxia and hypotonia. It is caused by mutations in the MKS1 gene on chromosome 17q23. The exact synonym for JBTS28 is Joubert syndrome type 28.

Joubert Syndrome 3, also known as JBTS3, is a type of Joubert syndrome that is caused by a homozygous mutation in the AHI1 gene on chromosome 6q23.3. It is characterized by distinctive facial features and intellectual disability.

Joubert syndrome, also known as JBTS4, is a genetic disorder that affects the development of the cerebellum and brain stem. It is caused by mutations in the NPHP1 gene on chromosome 2q13. This leads to abnormal development of cilia and flagella in cells within these structures, resulting in various symptoms such as ataxia, nystagmus, and hearing loss. Joubert syndrome can also be diagnosed through imaging techniques such as MRI or CT scans, which can reveal the characteristic "molar tooth sign" on the brain. Treatment for Joubert syndrome is primarily symptomatic, focusing on managing the individual's symptoms and improving their quality of life.

Joubert Syndrome 5 (JBTS5) is a type of Joubert syndrome, a genetic disorder that affects the development of the cerebellum and brain stem. It is caused by a mutation in the CEP290 gene on chromosome 12q21.

Joubert syndrome type 6, also known as JBTS6, is a genetic disorder characterized by cerebellar hypoplasia or underdevelopment of the cerebellum, which is responsible for coordinating balance and movement. It is caused by mutations in the TMEM67 gene on chromosome 8q22.
Joubert syndrome 7, also known as JBTS7, is a type of Joubert syndrome characterized by a mutation in the RPGRIP1L gene located on chromosome 16q12.2.

Joubert syndrome type 8, also known as JBTS8, is a genetic disorder characterized by the presence of a unique set of craniofacial features, including a prominent forehead, large ears, and deep-set eyes. It can also cause developmental delays and other health issues due to mutations in the ARL13B gene on chromosome 3q11.1-q11.2.

Joubert Syndrome 9 (JBTS9) is a type of Joubert syndrome that has a genetic basis, specifically due to mutations in the CC2D2A gene on chromosome 4p15. It is considered a digenic disease, which means it has a material basis in both homozygous and compound heterozygous mutation of this gene. The exact synonym for JBTS9 is Joubert Syndrome Type 9. Cone-rod dystrophy 2, also known as CORD2 or CRD2, is a type of cone-rod dystrophy that results from a heterozygous mutation in the CRX gene on chromosome 19q13. It has the same genetic basis as cone-rod dystrophy and is characterized by progressive vision loss due to degeneration of cone and rod photoreceptors in the retina.
It is also known as cone-rod retinal dystrophy 2 (CRD2) or retinal cone-rod dystrophy 2 (RCRD2).

Cone-rod dystrophy is a group of genetic disorders that affect the cone and rod cells in the retina. There are different types of cone-rod dystrophies, including X-linked cone-rod dystrophy 2 (COD2), which is characterized by vision loss due to the degeneration of cone and rod cells in the retina. It is caused by mutations in the COMP gene located on the X chromosome.

X-linked cone-rod dystrophy 2, also known as CORDX2, is a specific type of cone-rod dystrophy that has its basis in variation in the chromosome region Xq27. It shares similarities with other types of cone-rod dystrophies, but it has its own unique set of genetic and clinical features.

As with other forms of cone-rod dystrophy, the primary symptom of X-linked cone-rod dystrophy 2 is vision loss due to the degeneration of cone and rod cells in the retina. However, this type of dystrophy tends to have a later onset than some other forms and may not progress as quickly.

There is no cure for X-linked cone-rod dystrophy 2, but treatment options are available to help manage the condition and improve quality of life. These can include low vision aids such as magnifying glasses or electronic devices, and other supportive care measures such as occupational therapy and speech therapy.

It is important for individuals with X-linked cone-rod dystrophy 2 to work closely with their healthcare providers to develop an individualized treatment plan that addresses their specific needs and helps them maintain their independence and quality of life.

CORDX3, or Cone-Rod Dystrophy Type 3, is a type of cone rod dystrophy that results from mutations in the CACNA1F gene on chromosome Xp11. It is an X-linked recessive disorder, which means that it is passed down through the mother's family and can affect males more severely than females due to the way the gene is inherited. Symptoms of this condition may include progressive vision loss, cataracts, muscle weakness, and difficulty with balance and coordination.

X-linked cone rod dystrophy 1 (COD1) is a type of cone-rod dystrophy that has a mutation in the alternative terminal exon 15 of the RPGR gene on chromosome Xp11. It is characterized by progressive vision loss and retinitis pigmentosa, which are caused by defects in the photoreceptor cells in the eye. COD1 is inherited in an X-linked manner, meaning that it is passed down through the maternal line. Treatment options for COD1 include gene therapy and supportive care to manage symptoms such as visual impairment and night blindness.

Cone Rod Dystrophy 1, also known as CORD1 or CRD1, is a type of cone rod dystrophy characterized by abnormalities in cone-shaped cells and rod-shaped cells in the retina. It has a genetic basis due to variations in the chromosome region 18q21.1-q21.3.

Cone rod dystrophy 5, also known as CORD5, is a type of cone-rod dystrophy that has a mutation in the PITPNM3 gene located on chromosome 17p13.2-p13.1. It is characterized by progressive vision loss due to degeneration of the cone and rod cells in the retina, leading to night blindness and eventually complete blindness if left untreated. Genetic counseling and proper management of symptoms can help slow down the progression of this condition.

Cone-rod dystrophy 6, also known as CORD6 or RCD2, is a type of cone-rod dystrophy that results from a heterozygous mutation in the GUCY2D gene on chromosome 17p13.1. It has the same underlying cause as retinal cone dystrophy 2 (RCD2), and is characterized by progressive vision loss due to degeneration of the rod cells in the retina. Individuals with this condition may experience difficulty seeing at night, reduced color vision, and an increased risk of photoreceptor cell death. Treatment options for cone-rod dystrophy 6 typically focus on slowing the progression of vision loss and maintaining remaining vision, such as with low-vision aids or gene therapy.

Cone rod dystrophy 7 (CORD7) is a type of cone-rod dystrophy characterized by abnormalities in the cone and rod photoreceptor cells in the eye. It is caused by mutations in the NPHP6 gene, which is located on the short arm of chromosome 6 at position q13.1. CORD7 shares some similarities with other types of cone-rod dystrophy, such as congenital stationary night blindness and retinitis pigmentosa, but it has a unique genetic basis. The exact synonym for CORD7 is "cone rod dystrophy 7."

Cone-rod dystrophy 3, also known as CORD3, is a type of cone-rod dystrophy that is characterized by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ABCA4 gene on chromosome 1p22. It has the same material basis as cone-rod dystrophy 1 and is considered to be a distinct subtype of this condition.
It is important to note that there may be other synonyms for cone-rod dystrophy 3, but these are the most common terms used in medical literature.

Cone-rod dystrophy 8, also known as CORD8, is a type of cone-rod dystrophy characterized by abnormalities in the cone and rod photoreceptor cells in the retina. It is caused by mutations in the genes that are responsible for the production of proteins involved in vision.

Cone-rod dystrophies, including CORD8, are a group of hereditary disorders that affect the photoreceptors of the eye, leading to progressive vision loss. In CORD8 specifically, there is a variation in chromosome region 1q12-q24 that causes the abnormalities in cone and rod photoreceptor cells.

There is no cure for cone-rod dystrophies like CORD8, but early detection and management can help slow down the progression of vision loss. Treatment options include visual aids such as glasses or contacts, and medications to alleviate symptoms such as photophobia (sensitivity to light).

It is important for individuals with cone-rod dystrophies like CORD8 to work closely with eye care professionals to manage their condition effectively. With proper management, people with cone-rod dystrophies can maintain their independence and quality of life for as long as possible.

Cone-rod dystrophy is a group of genetic disorders that affect the cone and rod cells in the retina, leading to vision loss. Newfoundland cone rod dystrophy is a specific type of cone-rod dystrophy that has been identified in dogs, particularly those from the province of Newfoundland in Canada. It is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RLBP1 gene on chromosome 15q26. The exact synonym for this condition is NFRCD (Newfoundland rod-cone dystrophy).

Cone-rod dystrophy type 13, also known as CORD13, is a genetic disorder characterized by progressive degeneration of the cone and rod photoreceptor cells in the retina. It is caused by mutations in the RPGRIP1 gene, which is located on chromosome 14q11.2. The symptoms of CORD13 typically begin in childhood and may include vision loss, night blindness, and difficulty seeing in low light conditions. There is currently no cure for CORD13, but treatment options may include glasses, medications to manage symptoms, and other supportive measures.

Cone rod dystrophy 10, also known as CORD10, is a type of cone-rod dystrophy that results from a compound heterozygous mutation in the SEMA4A gene on chromosome 1q22. It is characterized by progressive vision loss and retinal degeneration, often leading to legal blindness by early adulthood if left untreated. There are no current treatments available for this condition, but research is ongoing to develop new therapies to slow down or halt the progression of the disease.

Cone-rod dystrophy 11, also known as CORD11, is a type of cone-rod dystrophy that results from a heterozygous mutation in the RAX2 gene on chromosome 19p13. It is characterized by progressive vision loss due to degeneration of the cone and rod cells in the retina. There is no cure for CORD11, but treatment options may include low vision aids, such as glasses or magnifiers, and gene therapy to replace the mutated RAX2 gene with a functional copy.

Cone-rod dystrophy 12 (CORD12) is a type of cone-rod dystrophy that occurs due to mutations in the PROM1 gene on chromosome 4p15. It is characterized by degeneration of the cone and rod photoreceptor cells in the retina, leading to vision loss. The exact synonym for CORD12 is "cone rod dystrophy 12".

Cone rod dystrophy 9, also known as CORD9, is a type of cone-rod dystrophy characterized by abnormalities in the development and function of cone cells in the retina. It has a genetic basis, with mutations in the ADAM9 gene on chromosome 8p11 being the most common cause. This condition can lead to vision loss and other complications if left untreated.

Cone-rod dystrophy 15 (CORD15) is a type of cone-rod dystrophy characterized by a homozygous mutation in the CDHR1 gene located on chromosome 10q23. It has been described as having a cone-rod dystrophy that has material basis in homozygous mutation in the CDHR1 gene on chromosome 10q23. CORD15 is also known by its exact synonym, cone-rod dystrophy 15.

Cone Rod Dystrophy 16, also known as CORD16 or Retinal Dystrophy with Early Macular Involvement, is a type of cone-rod dystrophy that affects the cone and rod cells in the retina. These cells are responsible for vision during daylight hours, and their damage can lead to severe vision loss.

Cone Rod Dystrophy 16 is caused by mutations in the C8ORF37 gene, which is located on chromosome 8q22. The condition can be inherited in an autosomal recessive manner or in a compound heterozygous manner, meaning that an individual must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the disease.

There is no cure for Cone Rod Dystrophy 16, but treatments are available to help manage its symptoms. These may include glasses or contact lenses to improve vision, low-vision aids such as magnifiers and reading machines, and medical therapies like steroids to reduce inflammation in the eye. In some cases, a vitrectomy (a surgical procedure to remove the vitreous gel from the eye) may also be recommended.

It is important for individuals with Cone Rod Dystrophy 16 to work closely with their healthcare provider to develop an appropriate treatment plan and manage their condition effectively.

Cone rod dystrophy type 17, also known as CORD17, is a rare genetic condition characterized by abnormal development of the cone and rod photoreceptor cells in the retina. These cells are responsible for vision and play an essential role in our ability to see in different lighting conditions.
Cone rod dystrophy type 17 is caused by mutations in the GNAT2 gene, which is located on chromosome 10 at position q26. The condition can be inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disease.
Symptoms of cone rod dystrophy type 17 typically begin in childhood and may include reduced vision, color vision deficiencies, night blindness, and progressive loss of visual acuity. In some cases, severe vision loss can occur, particularly if the condition is not properly managed.
Diagnosis of cone rod dystrophy type 17 typically involves a comprehensive eye exam, including visual acuity testing, color vision tests, and imaging studies such as optical coherence tomography (OCT). Genetic testing can also help confirm the diagnosis by identifying mutations in the GNAT2 gene.
There is no cure for cone rod dystrophy type 17, but treatment options may include low vision aids, such as magnifiers and glasses, to help individuals maintain their remaining vision. In some cases, gene therapy or stem cell therapy may be explored as potential treatments for the condition.
Overall, cone rod dystrophy type 17 is a rare genetic disorder that can significantly impact an individual's vision and quality of life. Early diagnosis and appropriate management can help individuals with this condition maintain their remaining vision and live as independently as possible.<|end_of_text|>

Cone rod dystrophy 18 (CORD18) is a type of cone-rod dystrophy characterized by the presence of homozygous mutations in the RAB28 gene, which is located on chromosome 4p15. CORD18 shares the same genetic basis as other forms of cone-rod dystrophy and is clinically indistinguishable from them. It has also been referred to as "cone-rod dystrophy, type 18."

Cone rod dystrophy 19, also known as CORD19, is a type of cone-rod dystrophy. Cone-rod dystrophies are genetic disorders that affect the cone and rod cells in the retina, which are responsible for vision. Specifically, CORD19 has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TTLL5 gene on chromosome 14q24. This dystrophy is characterized by progressive vision loss and night blindness. It is important to note that there are other types of cone-rod dystrophies, each with its own genetic basis and clinical presentation.

Cone-rod dystrophies are a group of genetic eye disorders that affect the cone and rod photoreceptor cells in the retina, leading to vision loss. Cone-rod dystrophy 20 (CORD20) is a specific type of cone-rod dystrophy characterized by mutations in the POC1B gene on chromosome 12q21. It can be inherited in an autosomal recessive manner or as a compound heterozygote, meaning that two different genetic mutations need to be present for the condition to develop. The exact synonym of CORD20 is cone-rod dystrophy 20.

Hemochromatosis type 2a is a specific form of hemochromatosis that is caused by mutations in the HJV gene, which is located on chromosome 1q21. It can be either homozygous or compound heterozygous for this gene. The condition is also known as HFE2A.

hemochromatosis type 4 is a form of hemochromatosis that is caused by a genetic mutation in the SLC40A1 gene on chromosome 2q32. It is also known as HFE4, autosomal dominant hereditary hemochromatosis, ferroportin disease, and hemochromatosis due to defect in ferroportin.

hemochromatosis type 1 is a genetic disorder characterized by the excessive absorption of iron from the diet, leading to iron overload in the body. It is caused by mutations in the HFE gene, which is located on chromosome 6p22. The condition can cause a variety of symptoms, including fatigue, joint pain, abdominal pain, and skin yellowing. In some cases, it may also lead to more serious complications such as cirrhosis, heart failure, and liver cancer. Treatment typically involves regular blood transfusions or chelation therapy to remove excess iron from the body.

Hemochromatosis type 3, also known as HFE3 or TFR2-related hemochromatosis, is a form of the disease that is caused by mutations in the TFR2 gene on chromosome 7q22. It is characterized by the presence of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in this gene. This type of hemochromatosis has a structural basis and can be diagnosed with a simple blood test that measures serum ferritin levels, which is a protein produced by the liver in response to iron stores. Treatment for this form of hemochromatosis typically involves removing excess iron from the body through phlebotomy or chelation therapy.

Hemochromatosis type 5, also known as FTH1-associated iron overload or HFE5, is a type of hemochromatosis that has a basis in a structural variant and is characterized by the presence of mutations in the FTH1 gene on chromosome 11q12. It is considered to be a rare form of hemochromatosis compared to other types such as hereditary or idiopathic hemochromatosis.

hemochromatosis type 2b is a form of hemochromatosis that is caused by a mutation in the HAMP gene on chromosome 19q13. It is also known as HFE2B. This condition leads to the overproduction of iron in the liver, which can cause liver damage and other health problems if left untreated. Hemochromatosis type 2b is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. Treatment for hemochromatosis type 2b typically involves removing iron from the body through phlebotomy and dietary changes.

African iron overload, also known as Bantu siderosis and iron overload in Africa, is a form of hemochromatosis characterized by the predisposition to iron loading that is exacerbated by excessive intake of dietary iron, commonly related to consumption of tradition beer brewed in non-galvanized steel drums.

hemochromatosis type 2 is a condition that affects the body's ability to regulate iron levels. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene for the condition to develop. This type of hemochromatosis typically causes severe iron overloading and can lead to various symptoms, including hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, cardiomyopathy, arthropathy, and liver cirrhosis or fibrosis. The condition is also known by several other names, such as HFE2, JHH, and juvenile hemochromatosis.

CADASIL (Cerebral Autosomal Dominant Arteriopathy with Subcortical Infarcts and Leukoencephalopathy) is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by migraine, strokes, and white matter lesions that have a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NOTCH3 gene on chromosome 19p13. CADASIL disjoint with cadasil 2.

cadasil 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, characterized by stroke, transient ischemic attacks, cognitive impairment, dementia, balance impairment, gait disturbance, headaches, and/or seizures associated with early confluent or confluent diffuse white matter hyperintensities that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the HTRA1 gene on chromosome 10q26. It is also known as autosomal dominant cerebral arteriopathy with subcortical infarcts and leukoencephalopathy type 2.

Glycine N-methyltransferase deficiency is a type of hypermethioninemia, which is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of persistent isolated hypermethioninemia without cystathionine beta-synthase deficiency, tyrosinemia type I, or liver disease that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GNMT gene on chromosome 6p21.
Hence, this condition is also known as hypermethioninemia due to GNMT deficiency or glycine N-methyltransferase deficiency.

Hypermethioninemia due to adenosine kinase deficiency is a type of hypermethioninemia that can occur in individuals with autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is characterized by developmental delay, early-onset seizures, mild dysmorphic features, and persistent hypermethioninemia due to a homozygous mutation in the ADK gene on chromosome 10q22. It is also known as ADK hypermethioninemia or MRT8. Additionally, it can be referred to as autosomal recessive mental retardation 8 and hypermethioninemia encephalopathy due to ADK deficiency or hypermethioninemia encephalopathy due to adenosine kinase deficiency.

Hypermethioninemia with deficiency of S-adenosylhomocysteine hydrolase is a type of hypermethioninemia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of psychomotor delay, severe myopathy, hypermethioninaemia and elevated serum creatine kinase levels that has_material_basis_in compound heterozygous mutation in the AHCY gene on chromosome 20q11. This condition is also known as hypermethioninemia due to S-adenosylhomocysteine hydrolase deficiency, and can be accompanied by psychomotor retardation as a result of this deficiency.

            owl:onProperty :has_material_basis_in ;

        :x_linked_recessive_disease ;
    :has_definition "A glycogen storage disease IX that is characterized by X-linked inheritance of variable exercise-induced muscle weakness or stiffness that has_material_basis_in mutation in the PHKA1 gene on chromosome Xq13." ;
    :has_exact_synonym "GSD IXd"@en,
        "GSD due to muscle phosphorylase kinase deficiency"@en,
        "GSD type 9D"@en,

text: Glycogen storage disease IX (also known as GSD IXd, GSD due to muscle phosphorylase kinase deficiency, and glycogenosis type 9D) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to store and break down glycogen. It is caused by mutations in the PHKA1 gene on chromosome Xq13, which leads to variable exercise-induced muscle weakness or stiffness. Symptoms can include muscle pain, cramps, and weakness, particularly in the arms, legs, and shoulders. Treatment may involve physical therapy, medications, and dietary changes.

Glycogen storage disease IXb, also known as GSD IXb or GSD due to liver and muscle phosphorylase kinase deficiency, is a type of glycogen storage disease characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of hepatomegaly, short stature, hypotonia, and accumulation of glycogen in both the liver and muscle without clinical symptoms. It has a basis in a compound heterozygous mutation in the PHKB gene on chromosome 16q12.

Glycogen storage disease type IXa, also known as GSD IXa or glycogenosis type 9A, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to store and metabolize glycogen. It is caused by mutations in the PHKA2 gene on chromosome Xp22, leading to an imbalance in the breakdown of glycogen.
Symptoms of GSD IXa include hepatomegaly (enlarged liver), growth retardation, elevated levels of glutamate-pyruvate transaminase and glutamate-oxaloacetate transaminase in the blood, hypercholesterolemia (elevated cholesterol levels), hypertriglyceridemia (elevated triglyceride levels), and fasting hyperketosis (elevated ketone levels). Symptoms typically develop in infancy or childhood and may improve with age.
Diagnosis of GSD IXa is made through a combination of medical history, physical examination, laboratory tests, and genetic testing. Treatment usually involves a low-carbohydrate diet, enzyme replacement therapy, and monitoring of liver function. Early diagnosis and treatment are important to prevent complications such as liver failure or other long-term health problems.
It is essential to consult with a medical professional for further information and guidance on managing this condition.

Glycogen storage disease type IX, also known as GSD IX or glycogenosis type 9C, is a rare autosomal recessive metabolic disorder characterized by the accumulation of glycogen in various tissues, primarily affecting the liver and skeletal muscles. It is caused by mutations in the PHKG2 gene located on chromosome 16p11. The symptoms of GSD IX typically begin in childhood and can include hepatomegaly (enlarged liver), hypotonia (weakness), growth retardation, and liver dysfunction. As the patient ages, the symptoms may improve or become less severe. Other synonyms for GSD IX include GSD type 9C, GSD type IXc, glycogen storage disease type 9C, and glycogenosis type IXc.

Gray platelet syndrome (GPS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the production of blood cells, specifically platelets. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that a person needs to inherit two copies of the mutated gene to develop the disease.
Symptoms of GPS include macrothrombocytopenia (large-sized platelets), enlarged platelets, myelofibrosis (a condition in which the bone marrow is replaced by fibrous tissue), splenomegaly (an enlarged spleen), and increased bleeding time.
GPS has been associated with homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the NBEAL2 gene, which is located on chromosome 3p21. The disorder is also known by other names such as BDPLT4, GPS, platelet alpha-granule deficiency, and platelet-type bleeding disorder 4.
Overall, GPS is a rare condition that can be challenging to diagnose and treat. However, with proper medical care, affected individuals can lead a relatively normal life.
Platelet Type Bleeding Disorder 9 is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

platelet type bleeding disorder 10 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that has material basis in some cases of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CD36 antigen gene on chromosome 7q21. It is characterized by variable bleeding tendency, thrombocytopenia, giant platelets, and prolonged bleeding times. The exact synonyms for this condition include BDPLT10, CD36 deficiency, and platelet glycoprotein IV deficiency.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 14 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to form platelets, which are essential for blood clotting. People with this condition have mutations in the TBXAS1 gene on chromosome 7q34, and as a result, they may experience abnormal bleeding, such as easy bruising, nosebleeds, and prolonged bleeding after injuries or surgeries. The disorder is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a person has an increased risk of developing the condition if one of their parents has it. There is no cure for Platelet type bleeding disorder 14, but treatments are available to manage its symptoms and prevent complications.

Platelet Type Bleeding Disorder 19 (BDPLT19) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to form normal blood clots. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the defective gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Symptoms of BDPLT19 include easy bruising, frequent nosebleeds, prolonged bleeding after minor injuries, and heavy menstrual bleeding. In severe cases, it can also cause ovarian cyst ruptures and abnormal megakaryocytic clusters. The disorder is caused by mutations in the PRKACG gene on chromosome 9q21.

Treatment for BDPLT19 typically involves managing symptoms with medications such as aspirin, clopidogrel, and vitamin K. In some cases, blood transfusions may be necessary to replace missing platelets. Genetic counseling is also recommended for individuals who may be at risk of passing the disorder on to their children.

Overall, BDPLT19 is a rare but serious condition that requires careful management and monitoring by healthcare professionals.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 17, also known as BDPLT17 or hereditary thrombasthenia-thrombocytopenia, is a type of autosomal dominant blood platelet disease. It is characterized by increased bleeding tendency, gray platelets, thrombocytopenia, abnormal megakaryocytes, and decreased or absent alpha-granules in the platelets. Additionally, it has a material basis in some heterozygous mutations in the GFI1B gene on chromosome 9q34.

quebec platelet disorder (BDPLT5) is a type of blood platelet disease characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of delayed onset bleeding after challenge, moderate to severe bleeding tendencies, frequent ecchymoses, mucocutaneous bleeding, muscle and joint bleeds and platelet alpha-granule degredation that has a material basis in heterozygous tandem duplication of the PLAU gene on chromosome 10q22.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 18, also known as BDPLT18 or bleeding disorder due to CalDAG-GEFI deficiency, is a rare autosomal recessive blood platelet disease characterized by mucocutaneous bleeding, prolonged and severe epistaxis, hematomas and bleeding after tooth extraction that has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the RASGRP2 gene on chromosome 11q13. It is important to note that this condition is not to be confused with other types of bleeding disorders, such as hemophilia or von Willebrand disease, which are inherited in a dominant manner.

Scott syndrome, also known as BDPLT7, SCTS, or familial prothrombin consumption inhibitor, is a rare genetic disorder that affects platelet function and can cause excessive bleeding. It is caused by mutations in the TMEM16F gene on chromosome 12q12 and is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 15, also known as autosomal dominant macrothrombocytopenia ACTN1-related, is a blood platelet disease characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of macrothrombocytopenia with little or no bleeding tendency and normal in vitro platelet function that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ACTN1 gene on chromosome 14q. It is defined as a condition where there is a decrease in the number of large platelets in the blood, with little or no tendency to bleed and normal platelet function in vitro. The exact synonym for this condition is BDPLT15, which stands for "Blood Disease Phenotype Ontology Term" for Platelet Type Bleeding Disorder 15.

von Willebrand's disease is a rare blood disorder that affects the body's ability to clot blood. There are three types of von Willebrand's disease: type 1, type 2, and type 3. Type 3 is the most severe form of the disease and is characterized by a virtual absence of VWF in plasma, prolonged bleeding time, and more severe bleeding tendencies compared to the other types of von Willebrand's disease. It is caused by autosomal recessive inheritance of a severe quantitative defect or virtual absence of VWF in plasma.

Platelet Type Bleeding Disorder 20 (BDPLT20) is a type of autosomal dominant blood platelet disease that has material basis in some genetic inheritance, and symptoms include increased bleeding tendency, thrombocytopenia, decreased dense granules and ATP secretion, and impaired megakaryocyte maturation. It is characterized by heterozygous mutations in the SLFN14 gene on chromosome 17q12. BDPLT20 also has an exact synonym of Autosomal Dominant Thrombocytopenia with Platelet Secretion Defect (ADT-PD).

Platelet Type Bleeding Disorder 3, also known as BDPLT3 or PT-VWD, is a type of autosomal dominant blood platelet disease characterized by the enhanced binding of von Willebrand factor by the platelet glycoprotein Ib receptor complex due to mutations in the GP1BA gene on chromosome 17p13.2. It has synonyms such as platelet type-von Willebrand disease, pseudo-von Willebrand disease, and von Willebrand disease platelet-type.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 11 (BDPLT11) is a rare autosomal recessive blood platelet disease characterized by mild to moderate bleeding and defective platelet activation and aggregation in response to collagen. The condition has a material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the GP6 gene on chromosome 19q13. BDPLT11 is also known as glycoprotein VI deficiency (GP VI deficiency) or platelet type bleeding disorder 11.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 12, also known as BDPLT12 or PGHS1 deficiency, is a blood platelet disease that is characterized by mildly increased bleeding, platelet aggregation defects, and impaired conversion of arachidonic acid to thromboxane A2 in platelets due to a deficiency in the activity of the enzyme PTGS1.

Bernard-Soulier syndrome type A2, also known as BSSA2, is a genetic disorder characterized by mild to moderate bleeding tendency, thrombocytopenia (low platelet count), and an increased mean platelet size. It is caused by heterozygous mutations in the GP1BA gene on chromosome 17p.

Ambras type hypertrichosis universalis congenita is a rare genetic disorder characterized by excessive hair growth on the body, particularly on the face, ears, and shoulders. It is caused by an autosomal dominant inheritance of chromosomal abnormalities in the region 8q22. The condition has been named after Andreas Ambrosius Hoffmann von Ambras, who was a physician from Austria known for his studies on hair growth.

This disorder can cause significant distress to individuals affected by it due to the excessive hair growth and the lack of control over their appearance. Treatment options are available, but they may not be entirely effective in addressing all symptoms. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to remove excess hair or improve the appearance of the skin.

It is important for individuals with Ambras type hypertrichosis universalis congenita to seek medical attention and support from a healthcare professional to manage their condition effectively.

Familial hypobetalipoproteinemia type 2 is a rare genetic disorder characterized by low levels of triglycerides and cholesterol in the blood. It's caused by mutations in the ANGPTL3 gene on chromosome 1p31, which can be inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern. The condition is also known as FHBL2 or combined familial hypolipidemia.

Familial hypobetalipoproteinemia type 1, also known as FHBL1, is a genetic disorder characterized by low levels of cholesterol and triglycerides in the blood. It is caused by mutations in the APOB gene on chromosome 2p24.

text: Hyperphosphatemic familial tumoral calcinosis is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by elevated blood calcium levels and the presence of calcium phosphate crystals in cutaneous and subcutaneous tissues. It has synonyms such as HFTC, HHS, PHPTC, cortical hyperostosis with hyperphosphatemia, familial Teutschlaender disease, familial hyperphosphatemic tumoral calcinosis/hyperphosphatemic hyperostosis syndrome, and lipocalcinogranulomatosis. It is also known as primary hyperphosphatemic tumoral calcinosis and tumoral calcinosis with hyperphosphatemia.

autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 1 is a type of autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy. It is characterized by spinal muscular atrophy, which is severe and results in respiratory distress that predominantly involves the upper limbs and distal muscles. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the IGHMBP2 gene on chromosome 11q13. The condition is also known by several other names, such as DSMA1, SIANRF, SMARD1, autosomal recessive distal spinal muscular atrophy 1, autosomal recessive spinal muscular atrophy with respiratory distress, diaphragmatic spinal muscular atrophy, distal hereditary motor neuropathy type 6, distal spinal muscular atrophy 1, distal-HMN type 6, severe infantile axonal neuropathy with respiratory failure type 1, and spinal muscular atrophy with respiratory distress type 1.

autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the muscles and nerves. It is characterized by progressive muscle weakness and atrophy, primarily in the arms, legs, neck, back, and torso. The condition typically begins in childhood or adolescence and can lead to significant disability if left untreated. It is caused by a mutation in the SIGMAR1 gene on chromosome 9p13.

Congenital bile acid synthesis defect 5, also known as CBAS5, is a type of congenital bile acid synthesis defect that has several characteristic symptoms. These include left upper quadrant abdominal rigidity and liver fibrosis. Additionally, it can cause splenomegaly and elevated levels of bile acid intermediates in the blood. CBAS5 is caused by a homozygous mutation in the ABCD3 gene located on chromosome 1p21.

Congenital bile acid synthesis defect 6 is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the decreased production of bile acids, which are essential for proper digestion and absorption of fat-soluble vitamins. It is caused by mutations in the ACOX2 gene on chromosome 3p14. The symptoms may include jaundice, steatorrhea (fatty stools), vomiting, and poor growth. Diagnosis can be made through blood tests that measure bile acid levels, imaging studies like ultrasound or MRI, and genetic testing to identify the ACOX2 gene mutation. Treatment typically involves dietary modifications such as a low-fat, high-fiber diet and supplements, medications to help absorb bile acids, and in some cases, surgery to remove the damaged liver tissue.

Congenital bile acid synthesis defect 4, also known as CBAS4, is a genetic disorder that affects the way the liver produces bile acids. It leads to intrahepatic cholestasis, which means that the liver can't remove bile from the blood properly. This results in malabsorption of fat and fat-soluble vitamins, low levels of serum cholesterol, and increased levels of THCA (trihydroxycoprostanic acid) in bile, serum, and urine. CBAS4 is caused by a homozygous mutation in the AMACR gene on chromosome 5p13. It has also been referred to as intrahepatic cholestasis with defective conversion of trihydroxycoprostanic acid to cholic acid and trihydroxycoprostanic acid in bile.

Congenital Bile Acid Synthesis Defect 2 (CBAS2) is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the absence of functional delta(4)-3-oxosteroid 5-beta-reductase, which results in impaired bile acid synthesis. This leads to severe cholestatic liver disease with rapid progression and complications such as malabsorption of fat and fat-soluble vitamins. It is caused by mutations in the AKR1D1 gene on chromosome 7q33, which encodes for the delta(4)-3-oxosteroid 5-beta-reductase enzyme.
