Oligomeganephronia is a type of renal hypoplasia characterized by bilateral reduced kidney size with a marked decrease in the total number of nephrons. It has exact synonym Oligomeganephronic renal hypoplasia.

Mitochondrial Complex V ATP Synthase Deficiency is a condition where one or more of the proteins that make up the mitochondrial proton-transporting ATP synthase complex are impaired. This leads to an issue with ATP production, which can impact various aspects of cellular metabolism and result in a range of symptoms depending on the severity of the deficiency.

Preterm premature rupture of the membranes (PPROM) is a condition in which the amniotic sac surrounding a developing fetus breaks down before 37 weeks of gestation. This can lead to complications for both the mother and the baby, such as infection or difficulty breathing for the newborn. It is important for women who experience PPROM to receive proper medical care to ensure the health and safety of both themselves and their unborn child.
ureteropelvic junction obstruction is a type of urinary tract obstruction characterized by a blockage at the renal pelvis where the kidney attaches to the ureter.

Acquired von Willebrand Syndrome (AVWS) is a type of blood coagulation disease that is characterized by the development of a defect in clotting in the absence of previous bleeding symptoms, negative familial history, and occurrence in a relatively older age. It typically develops secondary to other disorders such as lymphoproliferative, myeloproliferative, cardiovascular, and autoimmune disorders. AVWS is also known as Acquired Hemophilia A without Factor VIII.

Angioimmunoblastic T-cell lymphoma (AITL) is a type of peripheral T-cell lymphoma with poor prognosis. It is characterized by the presence of tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes, which are activated and have an autoimmune phenotype. AITL typically affects adults and has a higher incidence in males than females. The symptoms of AITL can vary widely depending on the organs involved but often include fever, night sweats, weight loss, and fatigue. Treatment options for AITL may include chemotherapy, immunotherapy, and/or stem cell transplantation. It is important to consult a medical professional for proper diagnosis and treatment of this condition.

Isolated ectopia lentis (IEL) is a type of lens disease characterized by abnormal stretching of the zonular fibers, leading to dislocation of the lens. This condition may be mild to severe and can progress with age. It has an exact synonym of familial ectopia lentis (FEL).

Autosomal recessive isolated ectopia lentis 2 (ARIEL2) is a type of autosomal recessive disease. ARIEL2 is a form of isolated ectopia lentis, characterized by the displacement of the lens from its normal position in the eye. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ADAMTSL4 gene on chromosome 1q21. ARIEL2 is also known as ECTOL2.

ECTOL1 is a genetic disorder that affects the lens of the eye. It is caused by mutations in the FBN1 gene, which is located on chromosome 15q21. This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that a single copy of the mutated gene is enough to cause the disorder. Symptoms can include nearsightedness, farsightedness, and cataracts. Treatment may involve glasses or contact lenses to correct vision and surgery to remove cataracts if they develop.

Prinzmetal's angina is a type of coronary artery vasospasm, characterized by spasms of the coronary arteries that occur while at rest, generally late at night or early in the morning, resulting in severe chest pain with preserved exercise capacity. It has some other synonyms too: Prinzmetal's variant angina, angina inversa, variant angina pectoris, etc.

Multicentric Castleman disease is a type of Castleman disease characterized by systemic inflammatory symptoms, polyclonal lymphoproliferation, cytopenias, and multiple organ system dysfunction caused by a cytokine storm often including interleukin-6. It has exact synonyms such as MCD, PMCD, giant lymph node hyperplasia, and plasmablastic multicentric Castleman disease.

Congenital mirror movement disorder is a type of physical disorder that is characterized by involuntary movements of one side of the body that mirror intentional movements on the opposite side, primarily involving the upper limbs. It has an exact synonym in familial congenital controlateral synkinesia and hereditary congenital mirror movements. Is there anything else I can help you with?

Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS) is a condition characterized by symptoms that occur upon standing or sitting up from a lying down position. These symptoms may include dizziness, nausea, fainting, heart palpitations, and shortness of breath. POTS can be caused by various factors such as dehydration, medication side effects, low blood sugar, and certain infections or illnesses. In some cases, it is also associated with a genetic mutation in the SLC6A2 gene on chromosome 16q12.2, leading to a deficiency of the norepinephrine transporter (NET). This can cause an excessive release of norepinephrine, which increases heart rate and blood pressure upon standing. POTS is not uncommon in military personnel who experience prolonged periods of sitting or bed rest, as well as in civilian populations. Treatment for POTS typically includes lifestyle modifications such as exercise, pacing activities, and staying hydrated, as well as medication to manage symptoms.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 21 (ARSCA21) is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia that occurs due to mutations in the SCYL1 gene on chromosome 11q13. It has an exact synonym called SCAR21 and can also be referred to as acute infantile liver failure-cerebellar ataxia-peripheral sensory motor neuropathy syndrome or autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 21 with hepatopathy. It is characterized by cerebellar atrophy, spinal cord degeneration and peripheral neuropathy.

Spermatogenic failure 9 (SF9) is a type of male infertility that is caused by globozoospermia, which is characterized by the presence of round-headed spermatozoa lacking an acrosome. This condition has a genetic basis and can be inherited from one's parents in an autosomal recessive manner. In other words, if both of your parents pass on the faulty gene, you will have a higher chance of developing SF9. The DPY19L2 gene on chromosome 12q14 has been identified as the mutation responsible for this condition.
It is important to note that while there may be some debate about its exact definition and synonyms, at least it does have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It's also worth mentioning that this type of infertility can be treated through various assisted reproduction techniques such as IVF or ICSI.

Castleman disease is a type of lymphoproliferative syndrome characterized by the presence of one or more enlarged lymph nodes containing cells with hyaline-vascular, plasmacytic, or mixed appearance microscopically. The exact synonyms for Castleman disease include angiofollicular lymph hyperplasia, angiofollicular lymph node hyperplasia, giant lymph node hyperplasia, and lymphoid hamartoma.

Saddan, also known as SADDAN dysplasia or severe achondroplasia with developmental delay and acanthosis nigricans, is a syndrome characterized by the presence of severe achondroplasia, developmental delay, and acanthosis nigricans. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the FGFR3 gene on chromosome 4p16.

The term "partial trisomy distal 4q" refers to a chromosomal disorder where there is an extra copy of the distal portion of chromosome 4q. This condition can cause various symptoms such as growth retardation, muscle hypotonia, intellectual disability, and craniofacial abnormalities. The condition has been described as having a material basis in duplication of the distal portion of chromosome 4q.

Camptodactyly, tall stature scoliosis hearing loss syndrome is a type of autosomal genetic disease that has material basis in some autosomal inheritance. It is characterized by the presence of camptodactyly, tall stature, scoliosis and hearing loss. This condition has been given the name CATSHL syndrome.

Crouzon syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of bones in the skull and face. It is caused by mutations in the FGFR3 gene, which is located on chromosome 4p16.2. The primary features of Crouzon syndrome include premature fusion of cranial sutures, hypertelorism (widened space between the eyes), a prominent forehead, and mandibular prognathism (an underbite).

Acanthosis nigricans is a skin condition characterized by the thickening and darkening of the skin. It is often seen in people with obesity or other medical conditions such as diabetes or hypothyroidism. In some cases, it can be a sign of an underlying health issue.

Crouzon syndrome acanthosis nigricans syndrome (CAN) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of bones in the skull and face, as well as the skin. It is caused by mutations in the FGFR3 gene, which can lead to premature fusion of cranial sutures, hypertelorism, a prominent forehead, mandibular prognathism, and acanthosis nigricans.

It's important to note that Crouzon syndrome is not the same as Acanthosis nigricans, although some people with CAN may have features of both disorders. It is also worth mentioning that while the FGFR3 gene is responsible for Crouzon syndrome, it is also associated with other genetic disorders such as Pfeiffer syndrome and craniosynostosis.

Epidermal nevus is a skin condition that is characterized by the thickening of the epidermis, which is the outermost layer of skin. This thickening can lead to hyperpigmentation, or the darkening of the skin in the affected area. Epidermal nevus typically develops at or shortly after birth and is considered a non-cancerous growth. It can be found on any part of the body and can range from being small and flat to large and raised. Treatment options may include topical steroids, laser therapy, or surgical removal.

Molybdenum cofactor deficiency type B, also known as MOCOD type B or MOCODB, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to convert sulfite into a form that can be used by cells. This condition is caused by mutations in the MOCS2 gene on chromosome 5q11. It has an exact synonym of combined deficiency of sulfite oxidase, xanthine dehydrogenase and aldehyde oxidase type B or molybdenum cofactor deficiency complementation group B.

Molybdenum cofactor deficiency type A, also known as MOCOD type A and combined deficiency of sulfite oxidase, xanthine dehydrogenase and aldehyde oxidase type A, is a condition caused by mutations in the MOCS1 gene on chromosome 6p21. It is characterized by a lack of molybdenum cofactor, which is essential for various enzymatic reactions in the body. Symptoms may include neurological problems, gastrointestinal issues, and increased risk of infections. Treatment typically involves supplementation with molybdenum, as well as addressing any underlying medical issues.

Molybdenum cofactor deficiency is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to process certain minerals and vitamins. It is characterized by the accumulation of toxic levels of sulfite, which can cause neurological damage and encephalopathy over time. The absence of molybdenum cofactor leads to this condition. Molybdenum cofactor deficiency also has synonyms such as combined deficiency of sulfite oxidase, xanthine dehydrogenase, and aldehyde oxidase. It is essential to seek medical attention if you suspect that you or a loved one may have this condition.

Molybdenum cofactor deficiency type C, also known as MOCOD type C or MOCODC, is a genetic disorder that results from a mutation in the GPHN gene on chromosome 14q23. It is one of several types of molybdenum cofactor deficiency, which are characterized by a lack of function of the molybdenum cofactor, an essential component of various enzymes involved in detoxification of xenobiotics and maintenance of redox homeostasis.

MOCOD type C is a rare genetic disorder that can cause severe neurological symptoms, including ataxia, dystonia, pyramidal signs, and cerebellar atrophy. Additionally, it may also result in the accumulation of sulfur-containing compounds, such as methionine, which can damage tissues and organs throughout the body.

Diagnosis of MOCOD type C is typically made through a combination of clinical evaluation, genetic testing, and measurement of serum levels of sulfite and xanthine. Treatment may involve dietary modifications, such as a low-sulfur diet, and medications to manage symptoms and prevent complications.

It is important for individuals with MOCOD type C to work closely with their healthcare providers to develop an individualized treatment plan that addresses their specific needs and ensures the best possible quality of life.

Dyggve-Melchior-Clausen disease, also known as DMC disease, is a rare autosomal recessive genetic disorder characterized by severe spinal deformities (spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia) and other skeletal abnormalities. It affects the development of the bones in the limbs and the vertebral column, resulting in characteristic features such as clawed fingers, platyspondyly, abnormalities of the iliac crest, and intellectual disability. In addition to these physical symptoms, affected individuals also have mucopolysaccharide storage disease, which is evidenced by increased levels of certain mucopolysaccharides in their urine. The disease has a genetic basis, with mutations in the DYM gene on chromosome 18q21 causing the condition. Homozygous and compound heterozygous mutations in this gene are responsible for the majority of cases of DMC disease.

sepiapterin reductase deficiency is a genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to produce sepiapterin, a compound that is involved in the metabolism of tyrosine. It is caused by mutations in the SPR gene on chromosome 2p. The disorder is characterized by dystonia, which is sustained muscle contractions, and other symptoms such as axial hypotonia, oculogyric crises, delays in motor and cognitive development, severe dopamine and serotonin deficiencies. Sepiapterin reductase deficiency has exact synonyms like DRD due to SRD, SPR deficiency, SRD, dopa-responsive dystonia due to sepiapterin reductase deficiency.

Subcortical Band Heterotopia (SBH) is a type of congenital nervous system abnormality. It occurs when neurons in the brain migrate to ectopic locations, forming areas that appear as band-like clusters of white tissue beneath the gray tissue of the cerebral cortex. This condition is also known by several other synonyms, including HeCo, Band Heterotopia, Double Cortex Syndrome, Heterotopic Cortex, and Subcortical Laminar Heterotopia.

Autosomal dominant sensory ataxia 1 (ADSA) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the extremities, resulting in gait difficulties and instability, especially in dark conditions. It is characterized by sensory loss in the extremities and has material basis in heterozygous mutations in the RNF170 gene on chromosome 8. It is also known as Sensory Neural Ataxia Type I (SNAXI).

French Canadian Leigh disease, also known as Saguenay-Lac Saint-Jean type COX deficiency, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by metabolic and/or neurological crises, chronic hyperlactatemia, hypotonia, ataxia, mild facial dysmorphism, delayed development, and the development of lesions in the brainstem and basal ganglia. It is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the LRPPRC gene located on chromosome 2p21.

familial hemiplegic migraine 1 (FHM1) is a type of familial hemiplegic migraine that is commonly associated with cerebellar degeneration and has_material_basis_in heterozygous mutation in CACNA1A on 19p13. It also has exact synonyms such as FHM1, MHP1, and familial hemiplegic migraine1 with progressive cerebellar ataxia.

Familial hemiplegic migraine 2 (FHM2) is a type of familial hemiplegic migraine. It has the same defining feature as Familial hemiplegic migraine 1, which is that it is a recurrent headache disorder characterized by brief aura, but unlike FHM1, it has a genetic basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ATP1A2 gene located on chromosome 1q23.2.

FHM2 also shares some common symptoms with other types of migraine, such as episodic migraine and chronic migraine, including recurring attacks of moderate to severe pain. However, it is important to note that not all headaches are migraines, and FHM2 can be distinguished from other types of migraine by its specific genetic cause and characteristic symptoms.

In summary, Familial hemiplegic migraine 2 (FHM2) is a type of familial hemiplegic migraine characterized by recurring attacks of moderate to severe pain with a brief aura. It has a genetic basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ATP1A2 gene located on chromosome 1q23.2, and shares some common symptoms with other types of migraine, but can be distinguished by its specific genetic cause and characteristic symptoms.

Familial hemiplegic migraine 3 (FHM3) is a type of familial hemiplegic migraine, characterized by recurrent episodes of migraine with motor weakness or numbness on one side of the body. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the SCN1A gene on chromosome 2q24.3. FHM3 has also been referred to as MHP3 and is a distinct type of familial hemiplegic migraine.

Myopathy, lactic acidosis, and sideroblastic anemia 3 (MLASA 3) is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the early onset of transfusion-dependent sideroblastic anemia with failure to thrive, hearing loss, epilepsy, stroke-like episodes, and severe developmental delay. It has a material basis in a heteroplasmic mutation in MTATP6 encoded by nucleotides 8527-9207 of the mitochondrial genome. This condition is also known as MLASA3.

Myopathy, lactic acidosis, and sideroblastic anemia 1 (MLASA1) is a rare genetic disorder that results from mutations in the PUS1 gene. The condition is characterized by muscle weakness, lactic acidosis, and abnormalities in red blood cell production. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that to develop the condition, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent. There is no cure for MLASA1, but treatment can help manage its symptoms.

Myopathy, lactic acidosis, and sideroblastic anemia 2 (MLASA2) is a rare genetic disorder characterized by variable onset and severity of symptoms. It is caused by mutations in the YARS2 gene located on chromosome 12p11.21. The condition can cause muscle weakness, lactic acidosis (a buildup of lactic acid in the blood), and sideroblastic anemia (a type of anemia characterized by the presence of ringed red blood cells). The severity of symptoms can vary greatly between individuals and may include respiratory distress and cardiomyopathy.

Distal myopathy with anterior tibial onset is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the muscles in the legs. It typically starts during young adulthood and begins in the muscles of the shins and thighs, before spreading to other muscle groups. The condition has a material basis in mutations in the DYSF gene on chromosome 2p13. It is also known as DMAT or distal muscular dystrophy with anterior tibial onset.

Myofibrillar myopathy type 9, also known as Edstrom myopathy or HIBM-ERF, is a form of the disease characterized by slowly progressive muscle weakness in adults, primarily involving the diaphragm and resulting in respiratory insufficiency. It is caused by mutations in the TTN gene on chromosome 2q31. This myopathy has synonyms such as HMERF, Hereditary inclusion body myopathy with early respiratory failure, MFM-titinopathy, and autosomal dominant distal myopathy with early respiratory failure among others.

Distal myopathy 3, or MPD3, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the muscles in the arms and legs. It causes slowly progressive weakness and atrophy in the upper and lower limbs, making it difficult to use hands and walk. The exact cause of this condition is not known, but it has been linked to mutations in the HNRNPA1 gene on chromosome 12q13.

Distal myopathy 4, also known as distal Achilles disease-filaminopathy (MPD4), is a rare form of muscular dystrophy characterized by progressive weakness and wasting of the muscles in the legs, particularly affecting the hip and thigh muscles. It is caused by a genetic mutation in the FLNC gene on chromosome 7q32. The condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a single copy of the mutated gene is enough to cause the disease.

Symptoms typically begin in childhood or adolescence and may include pain, stiffness, and limited range of motion in the affected muscles. As the condition progresses, muscle weakness can worsen, leading to difficulty walking, running, and performing other activities that require strength and endurance.

There is no cure for distal myopathy 4, but treatment options may include physical therapy, occupational therapy, orthotics, medications to manage pain and inflammation, and in some cases, assistive devices such as wheelchairs or walkers. It is important for individuals with this condition to work closely with their healthcare provider to develop a comprehensive care plan tailored to their specific needs and goals.

Distal Myopathy Tateyama Type, also known as Distal Muscular Dystrophy Tateyama Type, is a specific type of autosomal dominant distal myopathy characterized by muscle weakness and was first described in the Tateyama region of Japan. It is caused by mutations in the caveolin-3 gene (CAV3) located on chromosome 3p25. This condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the caveolin-3 gene, and it's characterized by progressive muscle weakness and wasting, especially affecting the muscles of the legs and arms. It is important to note that this type of distal myopathy is one of several types of autosomal dominant distal myopathies, which are a group of inherited disorders characterized by muscle weakness and wasting in the distal (farther from the center) muscles of the body.

Facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy type 1 (FSHD1) is a specific subtype of Facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy, characterized by the contraction of the D4Z4 macrosatellite repeat in the subtelomeric region of chromosome 4q35. It has the exact synonyms FSHD1 and facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy type 1.

facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy 2 (FSHD2) is a genetic disorder characterized by progressive weakness and wasting of the facial, scapula, and humeral muscles. It is one of nine subtypes of facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy (FSHD), which is the most common form of muscular dystrophy diagnosed in adults.

FSHD2 is caused by a combination of genetic and environmental factors, with the most common genetic cause being a defect in the DUX4 gene on chromosome 4. Individuals with FSHD2 typically have a normal life expectancy if properly managed with physical therapy, medications, and other supportive care measures.

The symptoms of FSHD2 may appear at any age but are most commonly diagnosed in childhood or adolescence. They can include weakness in the facial, scapula, and humeral muscles; limited range of motion; and asymmetry in the face and shoulders. In some cases, FSHD2 may also affect the respiratory system.

There is no cure for FSHD2 at this time, but researchers are working to better understand the underlying mechanisms of the disorder and develop new treatments. With early diagnosis and appropriate care, individuals with FSHD2 can lead fulfilling lives despite their challenges.

Autosomal dominant adult onset proximal spinal muscular atrophy, also known as Finkel disease and SMAFK, is a type of spinal muscular atrophy that affects adults and is characterized by slowly progressive weakness in the proximal muscles of the body, such as the shoulders, arms, legs, and hips. It is caused by a mutation in the VAPB gene on chromosome 20q13 and typically presents with fasciculations (twitching or muscle contractions) and absent or hypoactive deep tendon reflexes without bulbar or pyramidal involvement. This condition has an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern, meaning that it can be passed on to offspring by a parent who carries the mutated gene. It is important for individuals with this condition to seek medical attention and receive proper treatment and support.
Erythrokeratodermia variabilis et progressiva 1, also known as e
x linked distal spinal muscular atrophy 3 is a type of spinal muscular atrophy.

Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy (ADHMN) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the spinal cord and the peripheral nerves. It is characterized by progressive muscle weakness, especially in the arms, legs, hands, and feet. The condition is caused by mutations in the DYT1 gene, which provides instructions for making a protein called dystrophin. Dystrophin plays an essential role in maintaining the integrity of the muscle cell membrane and helps to prevent muscle damage. When there is a deficiency or absence of dystrophin, the muscle cells become vulnerable to injury and can lead to muscle weakness and other symptoms associated with ADHMN.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by progressive distal motor weakness and muscular atrophy of the peripheral nervous system without sensory impairment. It is caused by anterior horn cell degeneration and has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The exact synonyms for this condition include autosomal dominant dHMN, autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuropathy, and autosomal dominant distal spinal muscular atrophy.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 7, also known as DHMN7A or Harper-Young myopath, is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy characterized by slowly progressive distal atrophy and weakness affecting first the upper limbs and later the lower limbs and vocal cord paresis. It is caused by heterozygous mutation in the SLC5A7 gene on 2q12.3.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 1 is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy characterized by progressive distal motor weakness and muscular atrophy of the peripheral nervous system without sensory impairment. It is caused by anterior horn cell degeneration, as a result of a 1.35-Mb DNA insertion on chromosome 7q34-q36.2, resulting in the production of a novel gene-intergenic fusion transcript, UBE3C-IF. This condition has synonyms such as HMN I, autosomal dominant distal juvenile spinal muscular atrophy type 1, dHMN1, distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 1, and distal hereditary motor neuropathy type I. It can also be referred to as spinal Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease 1.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 14 is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the DCTN1 gene on chromosome 2p13.1. It is also known by several other names, including Harper-Young myopathy and distal spinal muscular atrophy with vocal cord paralysis type 7B.

autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 5 is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy, characterized by onset of distal muscle weakness and atrophy predominantly affecting the upper limbs in the first few decades of life. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the GARS gene on chromosome 7p14. This condition is also known as DHMN5, DSMV, HMN5, distal HMN V, distal HMN VA, and distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 5. It can also be referred to as distal hereditary motor neuropathy type V or distal spinal muscular atrophy type V.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 12, also known as autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 5B and distal spinal muscular atrophy type VB, is a genetic disorder characterized by progressive weakness and degeneration of the peripheral nerves. It is caused by mutations in the REEP1 gene, which is located on chromosome 2p11.2. This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern, meaning that a single copy of the mutated gene is sufficient to cause the disorder. Symptoms typically begin during childhood or adolescence and may include muscle weakness, cramping, and atrophy (wasting) of the muscles in the arms, legs, and other parts of the body. There is no cure for autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 12, but treatments may help to manage symptoms and improve quality of life.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 2, also known as HMN II, is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy characterized by slowly progressive distal limb weakness and atrophy between the second and fifth decades of life. It has exact synonyms such as HMN IIA, HMN2, HMN2A, autosomal dominant adult spinal muscular atrophy IIA, distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 2, distal hereditary motor neuropathy type II, and spinal Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease IIA.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 3, also known as HMN IIB or DHMN type 2B, is a condition characterized by the gradual weakening and loss of function in the muscles that control movement. It is caused by a mutation in the HSPB1 gene on chromosome 7q11.23.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 4 (DHMN2C) is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy. It is characterized by the inheritance of only one copy of an abnormal gene, which leads to the development of the disease. DHMN2C has its basis in a heterozygous mutation in the HSPB3 gene on chromosome 5q11.2. This type of motor neuronopathy typically affects the arms, legs and torso, causing weakness and muscle atrophy. It is also known as distal hereditary motor neuropathy type 2C (DHMN2C), HMN IIC, HMN2C, and distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type IIC.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 6 is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy. It has been defined as a distal hereditary motor neuropathy that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the FBXO38 gene on 5q32. This condition is also known by the exact synonyms HMN IID, HMN2D, and distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 2D. It may also be referred to as distal spinal muscular atrophy with calf predominance.

Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 3 is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the muscles in the arms, legs and torso. It usually begins in childhood and causes muscle weakness and wasting. It has been linked to mutations in a specific region on chromosome 11 and is also known as distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 3 or dHMN3.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 9 (DHMN9) is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy characterized by juvenile onset of slowly progressive distal muscle weakness and atrophy affecting both the lower and upper limbs. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the WARS gene on 14q32.2.

Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 4 is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the lower motor neurons, causing muscle weakness and progressive weakness. It typically starts in early childhood and involves foot and hand muscles, as well as other proximal muscles. The condition has a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PLEKHG5 gene on chromosome 1p36.31. It is also known by several other names, including DSMA4, autosomal recessive distal spinal muscular atrophy type 4, autosomal recessive lower motor neuron disease with childhood onset, and distal spinal muscular atrophy type 4.

Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 5, also known as DSMA5 or young adult-onset dHMN, is a type of autosomal recessive disorder characterized by slowly progressive weakness and atrophy of the muscles in the lower extremities. It typically starts in adulthood, with symptoms such as gait impairment and loss of reflexes. The condition has a genetic basis, with mutations in the DNAJB2 gene on chromosome 2q35 being the most common cause.

autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 8 (DHMN8) is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy. It is characterized by congenital, non-progressive, predominantly distal, lower limb muscle weakness and atrophy with variable severity that has_material_basis_in heterozygous mutation in the TRPV4 gene on 12q24.11.. DHMN8 is also known as DHMN, HMN, autosomal dominant benign distal spinal muscular atrophy, congenital benign spinal muscular atrophy with contractures, and congenital nonprogressive spinal muscular atrophy. Additionally, it has been referred to as distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 8 and distal hereditary motor neuropathy type VIII.

Autosomal recessive centronuclear myopathy (AR-CNM) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the muscles, specifically those in the eyes and face. It occurs due to mutations in genes that are located on the autosomes, which are the pairs of chromosomes that an individual inherits from both parents. AR-CNM is a form of centronuclear myopathy, which refers to a group of disorders characterized by the presence of a central nucleus in muscle fibers. The condition has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and can be defined as a centronuclear myopathy that has this genetic background. It is also known as AR-CNM, which stands for Autosomal Recessive Centronuclear Myopathy.

Autosomal dominant centronuclear myopathy (AD-CNM) is a type of autosomal dominant disease.
Autosomal dominant centronuclear myopathy (AD-CNM) is a type of centronuclear myopathy.
Autosomal dominant centronuclear myopathy (AD-CNM) is a type of something that at least has material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.
Autosomal dominant centronuclear myopathy (AD-CNM) has a definition as a centronuclear myopathy that has_material_basis_in autosomal dominant inheritance..
Autosomal dominant centronuclear myopathy (AD-CNM) is the exact synonym for AD-CNM.

Yes, Friedreich Ataxia Type 2 (FRDA2) is a subtype of the neurodegenerative disorder Friedreich Ataxia. It is caused by a mutation in the 9p23-p11 chromosome region and has synonyms such as FRDA2. Do you have any further questions about this condition?

centronuclear myopathy 2 (CNM2) is a type of autosomal recessive centronuclear myopathy. It's characterized by muscle weakness and severe proximal limb weakness. CNM2 is caused by mutations in the BIN1 gene, which is located on chromosome 2q14.3. The exact synonym for CNM2 is "centronuclear myopathy 2."

Centronuclear myopathy type 6 with fiber type disproportion (CNM6) is a rare form of autosomal recessive centronuclear myopathy. It is characterized by slowly progressive muscle weakness that typically begins in infancy or early childhood. The condition has a genetic basis, with mutations in the ZAK gene on chromosome 2q31.1 being the primary cause.

In CNM6, there is a disproportionate involvement of specific muscle fiber types, which can lead to asymmetrical weakness and other unique features in affected individuals. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that an individual must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disease.

There is no cure for CNM6 at this time, but there are treatments available to manage symptoms and improve quality of life. These may include medications, physical therapy, assistive devices, and other support services. It is important for individuals with this condition to work closely with their healthcare providers to develop an individualized treatment plan tailored to their specific needs.

Centronuclear myopathy 5, also known as CNM5, is a type of autosomal recessive centronuclear myopathy characterized by severe neonatal hypotonia, respiratory insufficiency, and difficulty feeding. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SPEG gene on chromosome 2q35.

centronuclear myopathy 1 is a type of autosomal dominant centronuclear myopathy characterized by slowly progressive muscle wasting and weakness involving mainly the limb girdle, trunk, and neck muscles. It has material basis in heterozygous mutation in DNM2 on 19p13.2.

Centronuclear myopathy 4, also known as CNM4, is a type of centronuclear myopathy that is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the CCDC78 gene located on chromosome 16p13.3. There are no other known synonyms for this condition.

Centronuclear myopathy X-linked (CNMX) is a type of centronuclear myopathy. Centronuclear myopathy X-linked is defined as a centronuclear myopathy that has a material basis in X-linked inheritance of mutations in MTM1 on Xq28. CNMX is also known by the exact synonyms CNM, MTM1, XLCNM, XLMTM, and myotubular myopathy 1.

CFTD (congenital fiber type disproportion) is a rare genetic muscular disorder characterized by weakness and wasting of specific muscle groups, predominantly those that control eye movements. It affects approximately 1 in 36,000 to 48,000 live births worldwide. The severity of the condition can vary widely among affected individuals, with some experiencing only mild symptoms while others may be severely disabled or even life-threatening.
CFTD is caused by mutations in the gene for the muscle protein dystrophin. It is inherited in an X-linked manner, which means that it is passed down through the maternal line and affects males more frequently than females due to the way the X chromosome is inherited during meiosis.
There is no cure for CFTD at this time, but treatment may include physical therapy, assistive devices, medications, and in some cases, a feeding tube if an individual has difficulty swallowing. Early detection and intervention can help improve the outcomes of affected individuals.

Chromosome 3 linked frontotemporal dementia, also known as FTD3, is a type of frontotemporal dementia characterized by degeneration in the frontal and temporal lobes of the brain. It is caused by mutations in the CHMP2B gene located on chromosome 3p11.2. This condition is also known as amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 17.

sveinsson chorioretinal atrophy is an eye disease characterized by the presence of progressive bilateral retinal and choroidal atrophy leading to central vision loss. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in TEAD1 on 11p15.3. The disease has several synonyms, including HPCD, SCRA, atrophia areata, helicoid peripapillary chorioretinal degeneration, and the Icelandic type of peripapillary chorioretinal degeneration.

Congenital Muscular Dystrophy, Dystroglycanopathy Type A is a genetic disorder that causes muscle weakness and brain/eye anomalies. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner and is characterized by cobblestone lissencephaly, a defect in alpha-dystroglycan post-translational processing, and has material basis in the mutation of MDA5 gene. The exact synonyms for this disorder include Congenital Muscular Dystrophy-Dystroglycanopathy, MDDGA, Congenital Muscular Alpha-dystroglycanopathy with Brain and Eye Anomalies, Klissencephaly Type 2 with Muscular and Ocular Involvement.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A11 is a form of the disease that affects the muscles. It has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth, and it is caused by mutations in the B3GALNT2 gene. The exact synonyms for this condition include Walker-Warburg syndrome, MDDGA11, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A11.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A8, also known as MDDGA8, Walker-Warburg syndrome or muscle-eye-brain disease GTDC2-related, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A8, is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles and other organs of the body. It is caused by mutations in the POMGNT2 gene on chromosome 3p22.1. These mutations can result in homozygous or compound heterozygous variations, leading to abnormalities in the dystroglycan protein, which is important for muscle function and development.

Symptoms of this disorder can include weakness and atrophy of the muscles, as well as other organ system involvement such as eye and brain abnormalities. The severity of symptoms can vary greatly among affected individuals, ranging from mild to severe. Treatment options may include physical therapy, medications, assistive devices, and other interventions aimed at managing symptoms and improving quality of life.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A9, also known as MDDGA9 or Walker-Warburg syndrome, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the muscles and other organs of the body. It is caused by mutations in the DAG1 gene on chromosome 3p21.31. The condition can cause severe muscle weakness, developmental delays, and various other health problems. Some affected individuals may also have brain and eye anomalies.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy A14 is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GMPPB gene on chromosome 3p21.31. It is also known as MDDGA14, Walker-Warburg syndrome, or muscle-eye-brain disease GMPPB-related. Additionally, it can be referred to as congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A14.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy A7, also known as MDDGA7, Walker-Warburg syndrome or muscle-eye-brain disease ISPD-related, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A7, is a genetic disorder that occurs due to mutations in the ISPD gene on chromosome 7p21.2-p21.1. It is characterized by muscle weakness, developmental delays, and various eye, brain, and heart anomalies. The condition is often severe and can be life-threatening, with a high rate of infant mortality. Treatment options are limited, but early intervention and supportive care can help manage the symptoms and improve quality of life for those affected.

Congenital muscular dystrophy, also known as CMD, is a group of genetic disorders that cause muscle weakness and wasting. Dystroglycanopathy type A12 is one subtype of congenital muscular dystrophy and it has a basis in an abnormality during fetal development. The exact synonyms for this condition include Walker-Warburg syndrome, MDDGA12, muscle-eye-brain disease POMK-related, and congenital muscular dystrophy with brain and eye anomalies type A12. It is caused by mutations in the POMK gene, which is located on chromosome 8p11.21.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A3 is a specific type of congenital muscular dystrophy that has its basis in abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. It is characterized by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the POMGNT1 gene, which is located on chromosome 1p34.1. The exact synonyms for this condition include MDDGA3, Walker-Warburg syndrome, muscle-eye-brain disease, POMGNT1-related, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A3.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A1 is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles and other tissues of the body. It is caused by mutations in the POMT1 gene, which is located on chromosome 9q34.13. The condition has a range of symptoms, including weakness and degeneration of muscles, brain abnormalities, eye problems, and craniofacial anomalies. It can also affect the heart and other organs.

There are different types of congenital muscular dystrophy, each with its own specific set of symptoms. Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A1 is one such type, and it is characterized by the presence of brain and eye anomalies.

Treatment for congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A1 may include physical therapy, occupational therapy, and assistive devices to help with mobility. Medications may also be used to manage symptoms such as weakness and pain. In some cases, a wheelchair or other mobility aid may be necessary.

It is important for individuals with congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A1 to receive proper medical care from a team of healthcare professionals, including genetic counselors and specialists in neurology, orthopedics, and ophthalmology. Early diagnosis and treatment can help improve quality of life and manage the symptoms of this condition.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A13 is a specific type of congenital muscular dystrophy that has its basis in an abnormality in prenatal development or at birth. It is characterized by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the B4GAT1 gene on chromosome 11q13.2.

It is also known as MDDGA13, Walker-Warburg syndrome or muscle-eye-brain disease, B3GNT1-related, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A13.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A10, also known as Walker-Warburg syndrome or muscle-eye-brain disease, TMEM5-related, is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy that has a genetic basis. It is caused by mutations in the RXYLT1 gene on chromosome 12q14.2. The syndrome affects various body systems including the muscles, eyes, brain, and heart. Symptoms can include progressive muscle weakness, developmental delays, and distinct facial features. Diagnosis is made through a combination of genetic testing, clinical evaluation, and imaging studies. Treatment options may include physical therapy, medications to manage symptoms, and supportive care.<|end_of_text|>

Congenital muscular dystrophy, also known as CMD, is a group of genetic disorders that affect the muscles. It's characterized by weakness and wasting of muscle tissue, which can lead to severe disability if not treated properly.
Dystroglycanopathy type A2 is one specific type of congenital muscular dystrophy caused by mutations in the POMT2 gene on chromosome 14q24.3. It's also known as Walker-Warburg syndrome or MDDGA2, and it can cause a range of symptoms including brain and eye abnormalities.
The exact synonym for this condition is congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type A2, and it can also be referred to as congenital muscular dystrophy with brain and eye anomalies type A2.

Congenital muscular dystrophy with dystroglycanopathy type a5, also known as Walker-Warburg syndrome or MDDGA5, is a genetic disorder characterized by muscle weakness and eye, brain, and heart problems. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the FKRP gene on chromosome 19q13.32. The condition is also known as congenital muscular dystrophy with eye-brain-muscle disease, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type A with brain and eye anomalies.

Congenital Muscular Dystrophy, Dystroglycanopathy Type A6 is a form of the Congenital Muscular Dystrophy-Dystroglycanopathy type A. This condition has its basis in abnormalities that occur during prenatal development or at birth. It is characterized by a combination of muscle and eye problems, as well as brain abnormalities. The condition is caused by mutations in the LARGE gene located on chromosome 22q12.3. This form of Congenital Muscular Dystrophy is also known as Walker-Warburg Syndrome or Muscle-Eye-Brain Disease, LARGE-Related. Another name for this condition is Congenital Muscular Dystrophy-Dystroglycanopathy with Brain and Eye Anomalies Type A6.

acromicric dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of severe short stature, short hands and feet, joint limitations, mild facial anomalies, skin thickening, and bone abnormalities including delayed bone age, cone-shaped epiphyses, shortened long tubular bones, and ovoid vertebral bodies that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in FBN1 on 15q21.1. It can also be referred to as acromicric skeletal dysplasia.

Palmoplantar keratoderma and congenital alopecia 1 is a type of physical disorder characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance. It has been described as an ectodermal dysplasia with severe hyperkeratosis, congenital alopecia, and nail anomalies in some patients. The condition has been identified to have a basis in abnormalities in prenatal development or birth, and it is caused by heterozygous mutations in the GJA1 gene on chromosome 6q22.31. It is also known as PPK-CA, Stevanovic type, autosomal dominant palmoplantar keratoderma and congenital alopecia, and keratoderma-hypotrichosis-leukonychia totalis syndrome.

Palmoplantar keratoderma and congenital alopecia 2 is a type of ectodermal dysplasia that affects the skin on the palms of the hands and soles of the feet. It is characterized by progressive hyperkeratosis, which can cause the development of thick, scaly skin. Additionally, this condition may be associated with alopecia (balding), sclerodactyly (hardening of the fingernails), cataracts, and pseudoainhum formation. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene for the condition to develop. The condition has also been referred to by other names, such as CASS, PPK-CA, Wallis type, PPKCA2, and cataract-alopecia-sclerodactyly syndrome.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, also known as ALS or Lou Gehrig's disease, is a progressive neurodegenerative disease that affects nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord. It is characterized by muscle weakness and atrophy, difficulty breathing, and eventually death. The exact cause of ALS is not known, but it is believed to be a combination of genetic and environmental factors. There is no cure for ALS, but treatment options are available to help manage the symptoms and improve quality of life.

The statement is partially correct. Hypertension and brachydactyly syndrome, also known as type E brachydactyly with hypertension or HTNB, is indeed a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by severe salt-independent hypertension, age-dependent brachydactyly, an increased fibroblast growth rate, neurovascular contact at the rostral-ventrolateral medulla, altered baroreflex blood pressure regulation, and a higher risk of stroke when left untreated. The disease has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the PDE3A gene on chromosome 12p12.2. However, there are no exact synonyms for this syndrome as it is a unique condition with its own set of characteristics.

Cerebrocostomandibular syndrome, also known as CCM syndrome or CCMS, is a genetic disorder that affects the development of the face and jaw. It is characterized by severe micrognathia (small lower jaw), posterior rib and palate defects, and often intellectual disability. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the SNRPB gene on chromosome 20p13.

Uveal coloboma, cleft lip and palate, intellectual disability is a condition that is caused by a mutation in the YAP1 gene on chromosome 11q22.1. It is characterized by uveal coloboma (a congenital eye disorder), variable degrees of orofacial clefting, intellectual disability, and hearing impairment. This condition has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Parkinson's disease 3, also known as PARK3 or autosomal dominant Lewy body Parkinson's disease 3, is a type of late-onset Parkinson's disease characterized by an average age of onset of 59 years. It has a material basis in mutations in the 2p13 chromosome region and is defined as such. The exact synonyms for PARK3 include late-onset Parkinson's disease, autosomal dominant Lewy body Parkinson's disease, and autosomal dominant Parkinson's disease.

Parkinson's disease (PD) is a neurological disorder that affects movement. It belongs to the group of motor system disorders known as Parkinsonism, which can be caused by a variety of factors, including genetic, environmental, and pharmacological causes.
PD is characterized by the degeneration of dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra, a region of the brain that plays an essential role in movement control. The loss of these neurons leads to a decrease in dopamine levels, which results in motor symptoms such as tremors, rigidity, bradykinesia (slowness of movement), and postural instability.
PD is diagnosed based on a combination of clinical examination, medical history, and neuroimaging techniques such as MRI or CT scans. Treatment options for PD include medications to alleviate symptoms, surgery to destroy or disconnect the affected brain areas, and physical therapy to improve motor skills and maintain muscle strength.
In terms of genetic factors, PD is associated with several genes that have been identified through various studies. However, it should be noted that not everyone with a genetic predisposition will develop the disease, and environmental and lifestyle factors also play a significant role in determining an individual's risk for developing PD.
Therefore, while Parkinson's disease 21 (PD21) is indeed a type of autosomal dominant inherited PD, it is important to consider the broader context of genetic and environmental influences when discussing this complex disorder.

Eye abnormalities include juvenile subcapsular or cortical cataract, epiretinal membrane in a person less than 40 years old, and retinal hamartoma. text: Vestibular schwannomatosis is a type of schwannomatosis that affects the vestibulocochlear nerve, which is responsible for hearing and balance. It is caused by mutations in the NF2 gene on chromosome 22q12.2 and can cause bilateral or unilateral vestibular schwannomas, meningiomas, ependymomas, and specific eye abnormalities such as juvenile subcapsular or cortical cataract, epiretinal membrane in a person less than 40 years old, and retinal hamartoma. The disease has been revised by international consensus and is also known as acoustic neurofibromatosis, bilateral acoustic neurinoma, or central neurofibromatosis.

Neurofibromatosis 1, also known as NF1, is a genetic disorder that affects the nervous system. It is caused by a mutation in the NF1 gene on chromosome 17q11.2. People with NF1 may experience symptoms such as cafe-au-lait macules (brown spots), freckling of the skin, neurofibromas (tumors on nerve endings), and Lisch nodules in the eye, among others. The bone abnormalities seen in NF1 include sphenoid dysplasia, anterolateral bowing of the tibia, and pseudarthrosis of a long bone.

glutaric acidemia I, also known as glutaric aciduria type I, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the metabolism of amino acids. It is caused by a deficiency in the enzyme glutaryl-coenzyme A dehydrogenase (GCDH), which is responsible for the conversion of 3-oxoglutarate to succinyl CoA. This defect leads to the accumulation of toxic compounds, such as 3-hydroxyglutaric acid and glutaric acid, in various tissues of the body, including the brain, spinal cord, and muscles.

Symptoms typically appear during infancy or early childhood and can include developmental delay, muscle weakness, dystonia (involuntary muscle contractions), and seizures. As the disease progresses, it can cause serious neurological complications such as ataxia, chorea, dysarthria, and asterixis (an abnormal tremor that affects the wrists).

Diagnosis of glutaric acidemia I requires measuring the levels of glutaric acid in urine and plasma, as well as genetic testing to confirm the presence of a mutation in the GCDH gene. Treatment typically includes a low-protein diet, supplements with L-carnitine, vitamin B6, and folate, and medications to manage symptoms such as dystonia and seizures. In severe cases, enzyme replacement therapy or stem cell transplantation may be considered.

It is important for individuals with glutaric acidemia I to have a comprehensive management plan that addresses their specific needs and follows them throughout their lives. Genetic counseling and support from specialists can also help families navigate the challenges of living with this rare disorder.

mc kusick kaufman syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects a person's development. it is characterized by the presence of genitourinary malformations, polydactyly, and congenital heart or gastrointestinal malformations in infancy. the condition is caused by mutations in the MKKS gene on chromosome 20p12.2. it has also been referred to as hydrometrocolpos syndrome, postaxial polydactyly, and congenital heart malformation, among other names.

The term "hyperferritinemia cataract syndrome" refers to a condition in which there is an excess of ferritin protein in the blood, leading to early onset cataracts. This condition is typically inherited in an autosomal dominant manner and has been associated with mutations in the iron regulatory element located in the 5' untranslated region of the FTL gene on chromosome 19q13.33. The condition can be referred to by several other names, including Bonneau-Beaumont syndrome, HHCS, HRFTC, cataract-hyperferritinemia syndrome, hereditary hyperferritinemia with congenital cataracts and hyperferritinemia with or without cataract.

Gamma glutamyl transpeptidase deficiency is a rare genetic condition caused by the absence of an enzyme called gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT). This enzyme plays a crucial role in breaking down certain amino acids, which are building blocks for proteins. When GGT is absent or not functioning properly, it can lead to the accumulation of glutathione, an important antioxidant and detoxification agent, in the blood and urine. As a result, individuals with gamma glutamyl transpeptidase deficiency may experience various health problems related to oxidative stress and impaired liver function.

The condition is usually inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that both copies of the gene responsible for GGT must be mutated or absent for the individual to develop the disease. In some cases, a person with only one copy of the mutated gene may show reduced enzyme activity but not necessarily have symptoms of the condition.

It's important to note that gamma glutamyl transpeptidase deficiency can be mistaken for other conditions that also cause increased glutathione levels, such as alpha-fetoproteinemia or oxalosis. Therefore, it is essential to seek medical advice from a qualified healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis and treatment of the condition.

Pentosuria is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is also considered as an amino acid metabolic disorder, where the body excretes excess pentose L-xylulose in urine. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DCXR gene on chromosome 17q25.3. Therefore, it is also known as L-xylulose reductase deficiency, L-xylulosuria, PNTSU, essential pentosuria, and xylitol dehydrogenase deficiency.

postaxial acrofacial dysostosis is a type of autosomal recessive disease that presents with severe micrognathia, cleft lip and/or palate, hypoplasia or aplasia of the postaxial elements of the limbs, coloboma of the eyelids, cup-shaped ears, and supernumerary nipples. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in DHODH on 16q22.2. The condition is also known as Miller syndrome, POADS, postaxial acrodysostosis, acrofacial dysostosis, Genee-Wiedmann type, and mandibulfacial dysostosis with postaxial limb anomalies.

Phosphoribosylpyrophosphate synthetase superactivity is an inherited metabolic disorder that results from mutations in the PRPS1 gene on the Xq22.3 chromosome. These mutations lead to increased activity of the enzyme PRPP synthetase, which causes an excess production of phosphoribosylpyrophosphate and ultimately increases uric acid and purine levels in the body. The disorder can present with either a mild or severe form, depending on when symptoms begin to appear during infancy or later in life.

Fumarase deficiency is a rare genetic disorder that occurs due to the absence or malfunction of fumarase, an enzyme responsible for breaking down fumaric acid. This results in increased levels of fumaric acid in the body and can cause metabolic acidosis, brain abnormalities, and developmental delays. Fumarase deficiency is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner and can be diagnosed with a simple blood test that measures the level of fumaric acid in the urine.

Infantile cerebral and cerebellar atrophy with postnatal progressive microcephaly is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the brain, causing damage to both the cerebrum and cerebellum. It is characterized by progressive microcephaly, which results in a smaller head size, as well as intellectual disability and seizures. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MED17 gene on chromosome 11q21. It is also known by an exact synonym of postnatal progressive microcephaly, seizures, and brain atrophy.

combined malonic and methylmalonic acidemia is an autosomal recessive disorder that affects the metabolism of amino acids. It is characterized by elevated levels of methylmalonic acid and malonic acid in body fluids, which can lead to developmental delay and failure to thrive in children, and neurological symptoms in adults. The condition is caused by mutations in the ACSF3 gene on chromosome 16q24.3. It is also known as CMAMMA and combined malonic and methylmalonic aciduria.

Ruijs-Aalfs syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by genomic instability and susceptibility towards early onset hepatocellular carcinoma. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SPRTN gene located on chromosome 1q42.2. The syndrome is also known as progeroid features-hepatocellular carcinoma predisposition syndrome.

Boucher Neuhauser syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by spinocerebellar ataxia, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, and chorioretinal dystrophy. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PNPLA6 gene on chromosome 19p13.2. The condition is also known as Ataxia-Hypogonadism-Choroidal Dystrophy Syndrome.

Geroderma osteodysplasticum is a type of autosomal recessive genetic disorder characterized by premature aging, progeroid features, short stature and dwarfism, severe osteoporosis, vertebral abnormalities, spontaneous fractures, developmental delay, and mild intellectual deficit. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GORAB gene located on chromosome 1q24.2. The condition can be diagnosed through physical examination and genetic testing.

Hyaline body myopathy is a type of congenital myopathy characterized by the accumulation of ATPase and antibody-positive myosin in hyaline subsarcolemmal bodies in type I muscle fibers. It results from mutations in the MYH7 gene located on chromosome 14q11.2. The condition is also known as myosin storage myopathy.

Autosomal recessive hyaline body myopathy is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by the accumulation of abnormal muscle filaments in the sarcolemma, leading to muscular weakness and an increase in creatine kinase levels. It is caused by mutations in the MYH7 gene on chromosome 14q11.2. The condition has been referred to as congenital myopathy 7B and Myopathy, myosin storage, autosomal recessive.

Autosomal dominant hyaline body myopathy, also known as congenital myopathy 7A, is a type of hyaline body myopathy that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by the presence of hyalinated or glassy bodies in skeletal muscle, which can lead to weakness and muscle stiffness. The disease is caused by mutations in the MYH7 gene on chromosome 14q11.2.
Isolated sulfite oxidase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease.

Oliver McFarlane Syndrome (OMFS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the eyes and pituitary gland. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene for the syndrome to develop. The main features of OMFS include trichomegaly (excessive hair growth), severe chorioretinal atrophy (degeneration of the retina and choroid), and multiple pituitary hormone deficiencies. It is caused by mutations in the PNPLA6 gene, which is located on chromosome 19p13.2. OMFS has also been referred to as eyelashes long mental retardation, long eyelashes-intellectual disability syndrome, trichomegaly-retina pigmentary degeneration-dwarfism syndrome.

occipital horn syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the connective tissue in the body. It is caused by mutations in the ATP7A gene, which is located on the Xq21.1 chromosome. This leads to abnormal copper transport and can cause symptoms such as hyperelastic and bruisable skin, hernias, bladder diverticula, hyperextensible joints, varicosities, abnormal copper transport, and multiple skeletal abnormalities. The disorder is inherited in an X-linked recessive pattern, meaning that a male will have full expression of the disorder, while a female will be a carrier. Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome Type 9 (EDS IX) and X-linked cutis laxa are other names for this disorder.

NARP syndrome is a type of mitochondrial metabolism disease that affects muscle strength and vision. It is characterized by developmental delay, retinitis pigmentosa, dementia, seizures, ataxia, proximal neurogenic muscle weakness, and sensory neuropathy. The condition has a material basis in a heteroplasmic mutation in the mitochondrial gene MTATP6. It is also known as Neurogenic muscle weakness-ataxia-retinitis pigmentosa syndrome, Neuropathy-ataxia-retinitis pigmentosa syndrome, and neuropathy, ataxia, and retinitis pigmentosa.

Codas syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects various parts of the body, including the brain, eyes, teeth, ears, and skeleton. It is caused by mutations in the LONP1 gene, which is located on chromosome 19 at position p13.3. The syndrome is characterized by developmental delay and a range of physical abnormalities, including cerebral, ocular, dental, auricular, and skeletal anomalies.
It is important to note that the exact cause of this disorder may not be known in some cases, but it can be inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Speech Language Disorder 1 (SLD1) is a genetic disorder that affects the development of speech and language skills. It is characterized by severe orofacial dyspraxia, which makes it difficult for individuals with SLD1 to produce understandable speech.

SLD1 has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the FOXP2 gene on chromosome 7q31.1. The disorder is typically diagnosed in childhood and can have a significant impact on an individual's communication abilities.

There are several terms that can be used to describe SLD1, including articulatory apraxia, childhood apraxia of speech, developmental apraxia of speech, developmental verbal dyspraxia, and speech-language disorder type 1. It is important to note that these terms are often used interchangeably, although there may be subtle differences in how each term is used or understood.
Sensory ataxic neuropathy, dysarthria, and ophthalmoparesis (SANDO) is a type of autosomal recessive disease.

Mitochondrial trifunctional protein deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the functioning of mitochondria, leading to various symptoms such as cardiomyopathy, myopathy, neuropathy, liver disease, and metabolic acidosis. It has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the subunits of the mitochondrial trifunctional protein, HADHA or HADHB, located on 2p23.3. The condition is also known by alternative names such as TFP deficiency and TFPD.

Histiocytosis lymphadenopathy plus syndrome, also known as Faisalabad histiocytosis or HJCD, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the presence of histiocytes in various organs and tissues. Symptoms include hepatosplenomegaly, heart anomalies, hearing loss, hypogonadism, and reduced height. The syndrome has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SLC29A3 gene on chromosome 10q22.1. It is considered an autosomal recessive disorder.

That is correct. Psoriasis 7, also known as PSORS7, is a specific type of psoriasis that has a material basis in variation in the region on chromosome 1p that includes IL23R. It is characterized by inflammation and thickening of the skin, which can lead to discomfort and potential complications if left untreated. Treatment options for Psoriasis 7 may include topical corticosteroids, vitamin D analogs, retinoids, and biologics, depending on the severity and location of the condition.

Mucopolysaccharidosis type 1H/S, or MPS IH/S, is a genetic disorder caused by mutations in the IDUA gene on chromosome 4p16.3. Mucopolysaccharidosis IH (MPS IH) is a genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to break down and remove large sugars called glycosaminoglycans. This leads to the accumulation of these sugar chains in various tissues of the body, causing a range of symptoms and health problems.
MPS IH is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that both copies of the gene must be mutated or altered for the disorder to develop. When both copies are not working properly, the buildup of glycosaminoglycans can cause problems with multiple body systems, including the skeletal system, nervous system, respiratory system, and digestive system.
Symptoms of MPS IH can include coarse facial features, corneal clouding, hepatosplenomegaly (an enlarged liver and spleen), heart disease, and cognitive impairment. The disorder also shortens life expectancy.
Treatment for MPS IH focuses on managing the symptoms and treating complications as they arise. Enzyme replacement therapy may be used to help break down glycosaminoglycans, while other medications or treatments can address specific symptoms and complications.

Mucopolysaccharidosis IVA is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that a child must inherit two copies of the defective gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. It affects many body systems, including the skeletal system, which can lead to short stature and other physical abnormalities.
There is no cure for Mucopolysaccharidosis IVA, but symptoms can be managed with a specialized diet, enzyme replacement therapy, and other supportive care. Early diagnosis and treatment are essential in managing the condition and improving quality of life.

Mucopolysaccharidosis type IVB, also known as MPS IVB, is a genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to break down certain types of sugar molecules. This leads to the accumulation of these sugars in the lysosome, which can cause a range of problems for the affected individual.

MPS IVB primarily affects the skeletal system and the central nervous system, leading to bone deformities, joint pain, and limited mobility. There are treatments available for MPS IVB that can help manage the symptoms and improve the quality of life for those affected. These may include enzyme replacement therapy, where an artificial form of the missing enzyme is given through a specialized feeding tube, or drug therapy to slow down the progression of certain symptoms.

It's important to note that MPS IVB is a rare disorder, and not all healthcare providers may be familiar with it. If you suspect that you or a family member may have MPS IVB, it's crucial to seek medical attention from a qualified professional who can provide an accurate diagnosis and recommend appropriate treatment options.

MPS IIIB is caused by a deficiency in the enzyme N-acetylglucosamine-6-sulfatase (GNS), which is located on chromosome 12q14.3. Symptoms of MPS IIIB can vary widely depending on the severity of the enzyme deficiency and other factors such as age of onset, genetic background, and environmental influences. Common symptoms include:

- Progressive vision loss due to retinal detachment or deterioration of the optic nerve
- Dental problems, including cavities and gum disease
- Muscular weakness and joint pain
- Intelligence delays and behavioral issues
- Abnormal growth (e.g., large hands and feet)
- Gastrointestinal issues such as constipation and difficulty swallowing

MPS IIIB is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a child must inherit two copies of the defective gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder. Genetic counseling can be helpful for families with a history of MPS IIIB or other related conditions.

There is no cure for MPS IIIB, but early diagnosis and treatment can help manage symptoms and improve quality of life. Treatment options may include enzyme replacement therapy (ERT), dietary modifications, and other supportive care measures to address specific symptoms.
